[[Ben Simmons]]

CATEGORIES: 1996 births, Living people, Australian basketball players, Philadelphia 76ers players, Sportspeople from Melbourne

Benjamin David Simmons (born 20 July 1996) is an Australian professional basketball player. He plays for the Philadelphia 76ers of the National Basketball Association (NBA). He also played college basketball for one season with the Louisiana State University (LSU) Tigers. He was chosen with the first overall pick in the 2016 NBA draft by the 76ers. In 2018, he was named the NBA Rookie of the Year. He was given his first All-Star selection in 2019.

Simmons was born in Fitzroy, Melbourne, Victoria. His father, Dave, is an American-born naturalised Australian former basketball player.

[[Khamis Al-Dosari]]

CATEGORIES: 1973 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from brain cancer, People from Riyadh, Saudi Arabian footballers, 1996 Summer Olympics, 1998 FIFA World Cup players, 2002 FIFA World Cup players

Khamis Al-Owairan Al-Dosari (خميس العويران الدوسري‎; 8 September 1973 – 7 January 2020) was a Saudi Arabian footballer. He played as a midfielder.

Al-Dosari was born in Riyadh. He played most of his career for Al-Hilal and Al-Ittihad. He also played for the Saudi Arabia national team and was a squad member at the 1996 Summer Olympics and the 1998 and 2002 FIFA World Cup.

Al-Dosari died of brain cancer on 7 January 2020. He was 46.

[[Rosena Allin-Khan]]

CATEGORIES: 1977 births, Living people, Alumni of the University of Cambridge, English physicians, Labour MPs (UK), Members of the British House of Commons for English constituencies, Politicians from London, UK MPs 2015–2017, UK MPs 2017–2019, UK MPs 2019–, Women politicians

Rosena Chantelle Allin-Khan (born 1977) is a British politician and medical doctor. 

She has been the Member of Parliament (MP) for Tooting since the 2016 by-election. She also is the Shadow Minister for Sport for Jeremy Corbyn since October 2016.

In January 2020, Allin-Khan announced her candidacy for Labour Deputy Leader in the 2020 deputy leadership election.

[[Know Your Meme]]

CATEGORIES: Websites

Know Your Meme (KYM) is a far-left website and video series where various Internet memes and other online phenomena are documented, such as viral videos, image macros, catchphrases, internet celebrities and more. It also investigates new and changing memes through research, as it commercializes on the culture. Originally produced by Rocketboom, the website was acquired in March 2011 by Cheezburger Network, which, in 2016, was acquired by Literally Media. Know Your Meme includes sections for confirmed, submitted, deadpooled (rejected or incompletely documented), researching, and popular memes.

[[Reuben Hersh]]

CATEGORIES: 2020 deaths, 1927 births, American mathematicians, American philosophers, American academics, Writers from New York City, Writers from New Mexico, Scientists from New York City, Scientists from New Mexico, People from Santa Fe, New Mexico

Reuben Hersh (December 9, 1927 – January 3, 2020) was an American mathematician and academic. He was best known for his writings on the nature, practice, and social impact of mathematics. He was born in New York City. Hersh wrote a number of technical articles on partial differential equations, probability, random evolutions (example), and linear operator equations. 

He was the co-author of four articles in Scientific American, and 12 articles in the Mathematical Intelligencer. Hersh was best known as the co-author with Philip J. Davis of The Mathematical Experience (1981), which won a National Book Award in Science.

Hersh died on January 3, 2020 in Santa Fe, New Mexico at the age of 92.

[[Larry Gogan]]

CATEGORIES: 1938 births, 2020 deaths, DJs, Irish radio personalities, People from Dublin

Lorcan 'Larry' Gogan (6 May 1938 – 7 January 2020) was an Irish broadcaster. He worked for Raidió Teilifís Éireann (RTÉ). 

He was a disc jockey on RTÉ Gold having worked on RTÉ 2fm. His show was The Golden Hour, during which Larry played old classic songs.

[[Ahivarn]]

CATEGORIES: Hindus, Legends

Maharaja Ahibaran was the 12th century ancestor King of Baranshahr (Bulandshahr). The Modi/Barnwal and Rajvanshi communities claim descent from him. Ahibaran was a Sooryavanshi kshatriya, He is credited with the establishment of a kingdom of traders in North India.

[[Widows (2018 movie)]]

CATEGORIES: 2018 drama movies, Movies shot in Chicago, Illinois, Movies set in Chicago, Illinois, American heist movies, Movies composed by Hans Zimmer, American drama movies

Widows is a 2018 heist movie directed by Steve McQueen.

The is about four Chicago women who tried to steal $5 million from the home of a local politician in order to pay back a crime boss from whom $2 million was stolen by the women's husbands before they were killed in a botched getaway attempt.

It stars Viola Davis, Michelle Rodriguez, Elizabeth Debicki, Cynthia Erivo, Colin Farrell, Brian Tyree Henry, Daniel Kaluuya, Jacki Weaver, Carrie Coon, Robert Duvall, and Liam Neeson.

Widows was theatrically released in the United Kingdom on November 6, 2018 and in the United States on November 16, by 20th Century Fox. The movie had strong positive reviews.

[[Second-wave feminism]]

CATEGORIES: Feminism

Second-wave feminism started in the 1960s in the United States. It lasted for roughly two decades. During First-wave feminism, women wanted to get the right to vote in elections and to be treated equally to men when it cames to owning and heriting property. Second-wave feminism focused more on issues of sexuality (sex education, contraception, abortion, family planning) and  violence directed against women (domestic violence, rape, and Women's shelters). In many countries, there were also changes to the laws about divorce. 

In the 1980s, there were disputes among different feminist groups (known as Feminist sex wars), over issues of sexuality and pornography. These disputes started the third-wave feminism in the early 1990s.

[[American Academy of Arts and Letters]]

CATEGORIES: Manhattan, 1904 establishments, Museums in New York

The American Academy of Arts and Letters is a 250-member honor society. Its goal is to support excellence in American literature, music, and art. It is in the Washington Heights neighborhood of Manhattan in New York City. It is in Audubon Terrace on Broadway between West 155th and 156th Streets, with the Hispanic Society of America and Boricua College.

The academy's galleries are open to the public. Exhibits include paintings, sculptures, photographs and works on paper from contemporary artists chosen by its members. Also works by newly elected members and award winners are shown. A permanent exhibit of the recreated studio of composer Charles Ives was opened in 2014.

Musicians and engineers like to record live there because the acoustics are among the city's finest. Hundreds of commercial recordings have been made there.

[[Martin Bundi]]

CATEGORIES: 1932 births, 2020 deaths, Swiss historians, Swiss politicians, Swiss writers

Martin Bundi (19 October 1932 – 1 January 2020) was a Swiss historian and politician. He was a longtime member of the Social Democratic Party. He was a member of the member of the National Council from 1975 to 1995. He was also the National Council's president from 1985 to 1986. 

Bundi was born in Sagogn. He was married with five children. He died on 1 January 2020 in Chur at the age of 87.

[[Fermi-Dirac statistics]]

CATEGORIES: Quantum mechanics

Fermi-Dirac statistics is a branch of quantum statistics. It is named after Enrico Fermi and Paul Dirac. It is used to describe the macroscopic state of a system which is made of many simliar particles (Fermions). One example is to describe the state of electrons in metals and semimetals, to describe electrical conductivity.

Fermi-Dirac statistics makes the following assumptions:

The Fermi distribution tells with what probability, a Fermi gas, at a given temperature and energy level, will have a particle in the given state.

[[Charles Fletcher Lummis]]

CATEGORIES: 1859 births, 1928 deaths, American explorers, American historians, Journalists from California

Charles Fletcher Lummis (March 1, 1859, in Lynn, Massachusetts – November 25, 1928, in Los Angeles, California) was a United States journalist, and an activist for Indian rights and historic preservation.

[[Ball valve]]

CATEGORIES: Hardware (mechanical)

A ball valve is a kind of valve that has a ball in it, and the ball has a hole in the middle.

When the valve handle turns one way, the hole opens up the valve and water or gas can go through.

When the valve handle turns the other way, the ball blocks the water or gas, and the valve is closed.

[[Innsbruck-Land District]]

CATEGORIES: Districts of Tyrol (state)

The Innsbruck-Land District is a district in Tyrol, Austria. It encloses the statutory city Innsbruck, and borders Bavaria (Germany) in the north, the district Schwaz in the east, South Tyrol in Italy to the south, and the district of Imst in the west.

It has an area of 1,986.45 km². As of 2012, 167,339 people lived there. The administrative center of the district is Innsbruck.

[[Fakhruddin G. Ebrahim]]

CATEGORIES: 1928 births, 2020 deaths, Pakistani politicians, Pakistani lawyers, Pakistani judges

Fakhruddin G. Ebrahim, TI (Urdu: فخر الدين جى ابراهيم; 12 February 1928 – 7 January 2020) was a Pakistani politician and lawyer. He was born in Ahmedabad, Bombay Presidency, British India. 

He was the 24th Chief Election Commissioner of Pakistan on 14 July 2012 and resigned on 31 July 2013. From 1989 through 1990, he was the 18th Governor of Sindh Province. Before, he was the 2nd Attorney General of Pakistan from 1971 through 1977. 

Ebrahim died on 7 January 2020 at his home in Karachi at the age of 91.

[[Aleksandr Shirvindt]]

CATEGORIES: 1934 births, Living people, Russian movie actors, Russian television actors, Soviet movie actors, Soviet television actors, Soviet writers, Russian stage actors, Russian voice actors, Russian screenwriters, Writers from Moscow, Actors from Moscow

Alexander Anatolyevich Shirvindt (Александр Анатольевич Ширвиндт, born July 19, 1934) is a Soviet-Russian actor and screenwriter. He was honored with the People's Artist and Meritorious Artist of the RSFSR. He was born in Moscow. He appeared in Grandads-Robbers (1971), The Irony of Fate (1975), The Twelve Chairs (1976), Three Men in a Boat (1979), Station for Two (1982) and The Irony of Fate 2 (2007). 

He voiced Aramis in Dog in Boots movie.

[[Rankweil]]

[[Russell Bannock]]

CATEGORIES: 1919 births, 2020 deaths, Autobiographers, Aviators, Canadian centenarians, Canadian military personnel of World War II, Canadian writers, People from Edmonton

Russell "Russ" Bannock CAN GBR (November 1, 1919 – January 4, 2020) was a Canadian Air Force fighter ace during the Second World War. He was a chief test pilot for de Havilland Canada. He was born in Edmonton, Alberta. 

In 2011, he was made a member of the Order of Ontario "for his contributions to the aerospace industry".

Bannock died on January 4, 2020 at the age of 100.

[[Monarchy of Canada]]

CATEGORIES: Politics of Canada

The monarchy of Canada is at the main figure of Canada's constitutional federal structure and Westminster-style parliamentary democracy.

The monarchy is in charge of the executive (Queen-in-Council), legislative (Queen-in-Parliament), and judicial (Queen-on-the-Bench) branches of both federal and provincial jurisdictions.

The current Canadian monarch and head of state is Queen Elizabeth II, who has reigned since 6 February 1952. Elizabeth's eldest son, Charles, Prince of Wales, is heir apparent.

[[NPC (meme)]]

CATEGORIES: Internet culture

NPC is a meme. NPC is sometimes called NPC Wojak. The NPC meme is normally used to express that people who like the political left do not think for themselves.

The NPC meme looks similar to the Wojak meme. 

The NPC meme was made in July 2016 by an unknown person. 

The first NPC meme was uploaded to the website 4chan, and the idea behind the meme was explained there. 

The NPC meme is famous, and has been shown on many news websites, for example on The New York Times, The Verge, BBC and Breitbart News Network.

[[A Touch of Frost]]

CATEGORIES: 1992 television series debuts, 2010 British television series endings, 1990s British television series, 1990s crime television series, 1990s drama television series, 2000s British television series, 2000s crime television series, 2000s drama television series, 2000s mystery television series, 2010s British television series, 2010s crime television series, 2010s drama television series, 2010s mystery television series, Detective television series, English-language television programs, ITV television programmes

Punjabi has three major dialects.

1. Majhi- Thus is the prestige dialect of punjabi primarily spoken in Majha region of punjab

i.e Sri Amritsar,Lahore, Ferozpur etc.

2.Malwai-spoken in Malwa: ludhiana bathinda etc.

3.Doabi-Spoken in Doaba:Nawanshahr,Jalandhar Etc.

[[Still Open All Hours]]

[[Forest Park, Illinois]]

CATEGORIES: Villages in Illinois, Suburbs of Chicago, Illinois, Settlements in Cook County, Illinois

Forest Park (formerly Harlem) is a village in Cook County, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago, United States. The population was 14,167 at the 2010 census. 

The Forest Park terminal on the CTA Blue Line is the line's western terminal, located on the Eisenhower Expressway at Des Plaines Avenue.

[[Cicero, Illinois]]

CATEGORIES: Towns in Illinois, Suburbs of Chicago, Illinois, Settlements in Cook County, Illinois

Cicero (originally known as Hawthorne) is a suburb of Chicago and an incorporated town in Cook County, Illinois, United States. The population was 83,895 at the 2010 census.

The town of Cicero is named after Marcus Tullius Cicero, a Roman statesman.

[[Silvio Horta]]

CATEGORIES: 1974 births, 2020 deaths, American screenwriters, American television producers, American television writers, Gay men, LGBT screenwriters, Businesspeople from Miami, Florida, Suicides by firearm in the United States, Writers from Miami, Florida, Writers who committed suicide

Silvio Horta (August 14, 1974 – January 7, 2020) was an American screenwriter and television producer widely noted for adapting the hit Colombian telenovela Yo soy Betty, la fea into the ABC series Ugly Betty. Horta served as head writer and executive producer on the series.

He was born in Miami, Florida. Horta was openly gay. He was found dead in a Miami hotel room on January 7, 2020 after shooting himself, aged 45.

[[National Assembly (Ecuador)]]

CATEGORIES: Politics of Ecuador

The National Assembly (Spanish: Asamblea Nacional) is the legislative branch of the government of Ecuador that replaced the National Congress in 2009, under the 2008 Constitution. 

The current President of the Assembly is César Litardo, as of 2019.

Within Ecuador, the National Assembly has the power to pass laws, while appointment of judges to the National Court of Justice is done by a separate Judicial Council.

[[Oswaldo Larriva]]

CATEGORIES: 1946 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from leukemia, Ecuadorian politicians, Academics

Óscar Oswaldo Larriva Alvarado (1946 – 6 January 2020) was an Ecuadorian politician and academic. He was born in Cuenca, Ecuador. He was a member of the Socialist Party until 2006 and later became a member of the PAIS Alliance.

Larriva was a member of the National Assembly from 1992 to 1994 and again from 2013 to 2017. From 2007 through 2009 and briefly in 2019, Larriva was Governor of Azuay Province.

Larriva died in Cuenca on 6 January 2020 of leukemia at the age of 74.

[[Walter Learning]]

CATEGORIES: 1938 births, 2020 deaths, Canadian stage actors, Canadian playwrights, People from Newfoundland and Labrador, People from New Brunswick

Walter John Learning CM (November 16, 1938 – January 5, 2020) was a Canadian theatre director, playwright and actor. He was known as the founder of Theatre New Brunswick. He was born in Quidi Vidi, Newfoundland. He wrote a play based on the Christmas television special A Gift to Last. 

Learning died on January 5, 2020 at his home in Fredericton, New Brunswick at the age of 81.

[[Lunch atop a Skyscraper]]

CATEGORIES: Photography

Lunch atop a Skyscraper is a photograph taken at the top of the steelwork of 30 Rockefeller Plaza, during the construction of the Rockefeller Center in Manhattan, New York, U.S.A.. It was taken on 20 September 1932. The picture shows a group of workers not wearing safety equipment and eating on a beam at 840 off the ground.

[[Jennifer Johnston]]

CATEGORIES: 1930 births, Living people, Irish novelists, Writers from Dublin

Jennifer Johnston (born 12 January 1930) is an Irish novelist. She was born in Dublin. Johnston has won a number of awards, including the Whitbread Book Award for The Old Jest in 1979 and a Lifetime Achievement from the Irish Book Awards (2012). Her novel, The Old Jest, was made into a movie called The Dawning. Her other best known novels include: How Many Miles to Babylon?, The Christmas Tree, The Railway Station Man, The Illusionist and Grace and Truth.

[[Lincoln Chafee 2020 presidential campaign]]

CATEGORIES: 2020 United States presidential campaigns

On January 5, 2020, former Governor of Rhode Island Lincoln Chafee filed paperwork with the Federal Election Commission in order to compete in the 2020 United States presidential election as a Libertarian.

Chafee unsuccessfully campaigned for the Democratic presidential nomination in 2015. During his candidacy, Chafee criticized Hillary Clinton for her public support of the 2003 invasion of Iraq and her use of a private email server. 

In 2019, following his move to the state of Wyoming, Chafee registered as a member of the Libertarian Party, which he announced through an op-ed. 

On January 5, 2020, Chafee filed paperwork with the Federal Election Commission to form a candidate committee for the 2020 United States presidential election. Chafee has said he plans on making a formal announcement about his candidacy on January 8, 2020.

He ended his campaign on April 5, 2020 after failing to win any of the primary contests.

[[Teton Village, Wyoming]]

Teton Village is a census-designated place (CDP) in Teton County, Wyoming, United States. The population was 330 at the 2010 census. It is located near Jackson, Wyoming.

[[Infanta Sofia of Spain]]

CATEGORIES: 2007 births, Living people, Spanish infantes and infantas, People from Madrid

Infanta Sofía of Spain (Sofía de Todos los Santos de Borbón y Ortiz; born 29 April 2007) is the second child of King Felipe VI and Queen Letizia. She was born at Ruber International Hospital in Madrid, She was baptized at Palace of Zarzuela in Madrid.

She has an older sister, Leonor, whom she follows in the line of succession to the Spanish throne.

[[Infanta Elena, Duchess of Lugo]]

CATEGORIES: 1963 births, Living people, Spanish infantes and infantas, People from Madrid

Infanta Elena, Duchess of Lugo (Elena María Isabel Dominica de Silos de Borbón y de Grecia; born 20 December 1963) is the first child and elder daughter of King Juan Carlos I of Spain and Queen Sofía of Spain. She is the third in the line of succession to the Spanish throne. She has a younger sister, Infanta Cristina, and a younger brother, King Felipe VI.

[[Infanta Cristina of Spain]]

CATEGORIES: 1965 births, Living people, Spanish infantes and infantas, People from Madrid

Infanta Cristina of Spain (Cristina Federica Victoria Antonia de la Santísima Trinidad de Borbón y de Grecia, born 13 June 1965) She is the younger daughter of King Juan Carlos I and Queen Sofía, She was born at ORPEA Madrid Loreto at Madrid, She was baptized at church in Zarzuela Palace. 

2015 she is sixth in the line of succession to the Spanish throne, after her brother King Felipe VI's children, her sister Elena, and Elena's children.

From 2013 she was investigated and later tried for fraud relating to accusations of corruption involving a company owned by Cristina and her husband. In February 2017, she was acquitted.

[[Queen Sofía of Spain]]

CATEGORIES: 1938 births, Living people, Kings and Queens consort of Spain, Spanish infantes and infantas, People from Athens

Sophia of Greece and Denmark (Σοφία, Sofía; born 2 November 1938) is a member of the Spanish royal family who was Queen of Spain during the reign of her husband, King Juan Carlos I, from 1975 to 2014. 

She became queen upon her husband's accession in 1975. On 19 June 2014, Juan Carlos abdicated in favor of their son Felipe VI.

[[Felipe de Marichalar y Borbón]]

CATEGORIES: Spanish infantes and infantas, 1998 births, Living people, People from Madrid

''Don'' Felipe Juan Froilán de Todos los Santos de Marichalar y Borbón  (born 17 July 1998 in Madrid) is the elder child and only son of the Duchess of Lugo, Infanta Elena of Spain, and Don Jaime de Marichalar. Felipe is fourth in the line of succession to the Spanish Throne, after his mother.

[[Victoria de Marichalar y Borbón]]

CATEGORIES: 2000 births, Living people, Spanish infantes and infantas, People from Madrid

''Doña'' Victoria Federica de Todos los Santos de Marichalar y Borbón (born 9 September 2000) is the younger child and only daughter of the Spanish Infanta Elena, Duchess of Lugo, and Don Jaime de Marichalar. Doña Victoria Federica is fifth in the line of succession to the Spanish Throne, after her brother Felipe.

[[Frederica of Hanover]]

CATEGORIES: 1917 births, 1981 deaths, Deaths from heart failure, Deaths from surgical complications, Kings and queens, Greek people

Frederica of Hanover (Friederike Luise Thyra Victoria Margarita Sophia Olga Cecilia Isabella Christa; Φρειδερίκη της Ελλάδας; friðeˈrici ˈtis eˈlaðas; 18 April 1917 – 6 February 1981) was Queen consort of Greece from 1947 until 1964 as the wife of King Paul.

[[Princess Irene of Greece and Denmark]]

CATEGORIES: Princes and princesses, Greek people, People from Cape Town, 1942 births, Living people

Princess Irene of Greece and Denmark (Ειρήνη; born  11 May 1942) is the youngest child and second daughter of King Paul of Greece and his wife Princess Frederika of Hanover. She is the younger sister of Queen Sofía of Spain and of the deposed King Constantine II of Greece and maternal aunt of Felipe VI of Spain. 

[[Infanta Pilar, Duchess of Badajoz]]

CATEGORIES: 1936 births, 2020 deaths, Cancer deaths in Spain, Deaths from colorectal cancer, House of Bourbon, People from Cannes, Spanish infantes and infantas

Infanta Pilar of Spain, Duchess of Badajoz, Dowager Viscountess of la Torre (María del Pilar Alfonsa Juana Victoria Luisa Ignacia y Todos los Santos de Borbón y Borbón-Dos Sicilias; 30 July 1936 – 8 January 2020), sometimes known more simply as Pilar de Borbón, was a member of the Spanish royal family. She was oldest child of Infante Juan, Count of Barcelona and Princess María Mercedes of Bourbon-Two Sicilies. She was the older sister of King Juan Carlos I, Infanta Margarita and Infante Alfonso.

Infanta Pilar supported the sport of equestrianism. She served as the president of the International Federation for Equestrian Sports from 1994 to 2006. From 1996 to 2006, she was a member of the International Olympic Committee for Spain.

Infanta Pilar was born in the French city of Cannes. She lived most of her early years in exile from Spain. King Alfonso XIII, her grandfather, had been forced to flee with his family before she was born.

On 8 January 2020, Infanta Pilar died of colon cancer in Madrid. She was 83.

[[Sermersooq]]

CATEGORIES: 21st century establishments in Denmark, 2000s establishments in North America, 2009 establishments, Municipalities, Settlements in Greenland

Sermersooq (Greenlandic: seʁmeʁsoːq̚, place of much ice, sted med meget is) is the most populous municipality of Greenland. Its capital and largest city is Nuuk, also the capital and largest city of Greenland. It was created on 1 January 2009 and is made of five municipalities.

[[Barry Gardiner]]

CATEGORIES: 1957 births, Scottish politicians, British socialists, Living people, Harvard University alumni, UK MPs 1997–2001, UK MPs 2001–2005, UK MPs 2005–2010, UK MPs 2010–2015, UK MPs 2015–2017, UK MPs 2017–2019, UK MPs 2019–, People from Glasgow

Barry Strachan Gardiner (born 10 March 1957) is a British Labour Party politician. He is the Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade since 2016. He has been a Member of Parliament (MP) for Brent North since 1997.

Gardiner worked under Tony Blair and Gordon Brown as a junior minister in the Northern Ireland Office, the Department for Productivity, Energy and Industry, the Department of Trade and Industry and finally in the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs.

[[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]]

CATEGORIES: 2020 in Asia, 21st century in Iran, Aviation disasters in Asia, January 2020 events

Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752 was an airplane flight between Iran and Ukraine that crashed shortly after it flew away from Tehran Imam Khomeini International Airport on 8 January 2020. All 176 passengers onboard and its crew died. 

On 9 January 2020, it was reported that U.S. officials believed that plane was shot down by an Iranian Tor-M1 surface to air missile, probably by mistake.

On 11 January 2020, Iran said that it had shot down the plane by mistake.

[[Tomorrow (Silverchair song)]]

"Tomorrow" is a song by the Australian rock band Silverchair. It was released as the group's first single in 1994, and was later re-recorded for their 1995 debut album Frogstomp. It reached number-one on the charts in Australia, becoming their first of three number-one singles there.

It was written by the group's lead singer and guitarist Daniel Johns, as well as the group's drummer, Ben Gillies.

[[Freak]]

CATEGORIES: 1997 songs

"Freak" is a song by the Australian rock band Silverchair. It was released in January 1997 as a single, and was later released the next month on their second album, Freak Show. It reached number-one on the charts in Australia, becoming their second of three number-one singles there.

It was written by the group's lead singer and guitarist Daniel Johns, as well as the group's drummer, Ben Gillies.

[[Straight Lines]]

CATEGORIES: 2007 songs

"Straight Lines" is a song by the Australian rock band Silverchair. It was released on March 20, 2007 as a single, and ten days later it was released on their fifth and final album, titled Young Modern. It reached number-one on the charts in Australia, becoming their third and last number-one single there.

It was written by the group's lead singer and guitarist Daniel Johns, as well as Australian musician Julian Hamilton. "Straight Lines" is one of only four Silverchair songs to feature a co-writing credit by a non-member, the other three also being songs from Young Modern co-written by Johns and Hamilton.

[[Cass City, Michigan]]

CATEGORIES: Villages in Michigan

Cass City is a village in Tuscola County in the U.S. state of Michigan. In 2010, 2,428 people lived there.

[[Spaniel]]

CATEGORIES: Spaniels, Dogs, Working dogs, Hunting

A spaniel is a type of gun dog. Spaniels were especially bred in the 1700's in Great Britain to flush game birds out of thick bushes There are many types of spaniel dogs, the most popular ones are the Cocker Spaniel, the English Springer Spaniel, the Field Spaniel and the Welsh Springer Spaniel.

[[Vincenzo Cerundolo]]

CATEGORIES: 1959 births, 2020 deaths, Alumni of the University of Oxford, Fellows of the Royal Society, Immunologists, Italian scientists, People from Lecce

Vincenzo Cerundolo GBR (20 December 1959 – 7 January 2020) was an Italian medical researcher. He was the director of the Medical Research Council (MRC) Human Immunology Unit at the John Radcliffe Hospital. He was a professor of immunology at the University of Oxford. He was also a Supernumerary Fellow at Merton College, Oxford. He was known for his discoveries in processing and presentation of cancer and viral peptides to T cells and lipids.

Cerundolo was born in Lecce. He was married and had two children. He died in January 2020, at the age of 60.

[[Fealty]]

CATEGORIES: Feudalism

An oath of fealty is a pledge of allegiance of one person to another.

In medieval Europe, the swearing of fealty is an oath made by a subordinate to his lord. "Fealty" also referred to the duties that a servant need to perform. These includes service and aid.

[[Wolfgang Brezinka]]

CATEGORIES: 1928 births, 2020 deaths, Austrian scientists, German educators, Scientists from Berlin, Austrian educators, German scientists

Wolfgang Brezinka (9 June 1928 – 3 January 2020) was a German-Austrian educational scientist. He was born in Berlin. He served as professor of pedagogy at the Pedagogical University in Würzburg. He also worked at the universities of Innsbruck and Konstanz. He was a researcher at Columbia University and Harvard University.

On 3 January 2020, Brezinka died in Telfes, in the Austrian state of Tyrol. He was 91.

[[Prem Nath Hoon]]

CATEGORIES: 1929 births, 2020 deaths, Indian military people, Generals

Prem Nath Hoon (4 October 1929 – 6 January 2020) was an Indian military officer. He was the General Officer Commanding-in-Chief of the Western Command of the Indian Armed Forces from 1986 to 1987. He took part in the 1962 Sino-Indian War and 1965 Indo–Pakistan War. In 1984, he led Operation Meghdoot, the Indian Armed Forces operation to capture the Siachen Glacier in the Kashmir region. He was also part of Operation Brasstacks, the biggest military exercise since World War II. Hoon was born in Abbottabad, North West Frontier Province (now Pakistan). 

Hoon died on 6 January 2020 in Chandimandir, Haryana. He was 90.

[[George Perles]]

CATEGORIES: 1934 births, 2020 deaths, American football coaches, Deaths from Parkinson's disease, Disease-related deaths in Michigan, Sportspeople from Detroit, Michigan

George J. Perles (July 16, 1934 – January 7, 2020) was an American football player and coach. He was born in Detroit, Michigan. He was a defensive line coach, defensive coordinator and assistant head coach for the National Football League's Pittsburgh Steelers from 1972 to 1982. He was also the head football coach at Michigan State University (MSU) from 1983 to 1994. He was added to the MSU Board of Trustees in 2006. He retired from his position on the board in November 2018 due to health reasons and wanting to spend time with family.

On January 7, 2020, Perles died from Parkinson's disease in Lansing, Michigan. He was 85.

[[Yong Pung How]]

CATEGORIES: 1926 births, 2020 deaths, Bankers, Chief justices, Kuala Lumpur, Singaporean politicians

Yong Pung How DUBC DUT (First Class) (11 April 1926 – 9 January 2020) was a Singaporean judge. He served as Chief Justice from 1990 to 2006. Before being a judge, he was a lawyer, banker and senior government official. From 2010 until his death in 2020, he had been the Chancellor of the Singapore Management University. Yong was born in Kuala Lumpur, Malaya. He came from an ethnic Chinese family with Hakka ancestry from Dabu County, Guangdong. 

Yong died on 9 January 2020, at the age of 93.

[[Ayako Wakao]]

CATEGORIES: 1933 births, Living people, Actors from Tokyo

Ayako Wakao is a Japanese actress. She was born in Tokyo. She was a favorite actress of director Yasuzo Masumura, starring in 25 of his movies. She appeared in Kenji Mizoguchi's A Geisha and Street of Shame. She also appeared in Yasujirō Ozu's Floating Weeds. 

[[Thomas Gage]]

CATEGORIES: 1719 births, 1787 deaths, British Army generals, People educated at Westminster School, London

General Thomas Gage (10 March 1718/19 – 2 April 1787) was a British Army general officer and colonial official best known for his many years of service in North America, including his role as British commander-in-chief in the early days of the American Revolution.

Thomas Gage, on February 20, 1773, already communicated to the governor of Louisiana, Luis de Unzaga y Amézaga 'le Conciliateur', his intention to return to the United Kingdom with his family, a fact that occurred 4 months later, in June Therefore, Gage was not present when the Boston Tea Party took place in December of that year, a city in which both Gage and Unzaga left confidants to be informed by their respective spy networks.

[[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]]

CATEGORIES: February 2020 events, March 2020 events, April 2020 events, 2020 United States presidential election

[[2020 Democratic National Convention]]

CATEGORIES: 2020 United States presidential election, 21st century in Wisconsin, August 2020 events, Milwaukee, Wisconsin, United States presidential nominating conventions, United States Democratic Party

The 2020 Democratic National Convention was a presidential nominating convention held August 17–20, 2020 at the Wisconsin Center in Milwaukee, Wisconsin. 

At the convention, delegates of the United States Democratic Party formally chose former Vice President Joe Biden for president and U.S. Senator Kamala Harris for vice president in the 2020 United States presidential election.

Originally scheduled to be held July 13–16, 2020 at the Fiserv Forum in Milwaukee, due to the ongoing coronavirus pandemic in the United States, the convention was postponed to August 17–20, 2020, and was later shrunk its capacity, with its location moved to city's Wisconsin Center.

Due to the pandemic, the format was different from other conventions, with most of the convention being held remotely from many venues across the country. While being a largely virtual convention, it was officially centered at the Wisconsin Center, where its production was headquartered and from where it was gaveled in and out each night.

Joe Solmonese, former President of the Human Rights Campaign, was named convention CEO in March 2019.

Every living former Democratic president (Jimmy Carter, Bill Clinton, Barack Obama) gave a speech, as well as a number of Republicans, including former Governor John Kasich of Ohio. Former Secretary of State Hillary Clinton and Senator Bernie Sanders also spoke at the convention.

[[Infanta Margarita, Duchess of Soria]]

CATEGORIES: 1939 births, Living people, Blind people, House of Bourbon, People from Rome, Spanish infantes and infantas

Infanta Margarita of Spain, Duchess of Soria, 2nd Duchess of Hernani, Grandee of Spain (Margarita María de la Victoria Esperanza Jacoba Felicidad Perpetua de Todos los Santos de Borbón y Borbón; born 6 March 1939) is a member of the Spanish royal family. She is the younger sister of King Juan Carlos I and aunt of current King Felipe VI of Spain. Her parents were Infante Juan, Count of Barcelona and Princess María Mercedes of Bourbon-Two Sicilies. She also had other siblings, Infanta Pilar and Infante Alfonso.

Infanta Margarita was born in the Italian capital city Rome. She was born blind. Her family were exiled from Spain at the time of her birth. She has been married to Carlos Zurita since 1972. The couple have two children.

[[Chan Sek Keong]]

CATEGORIES: 1937 births, Living people, Attorneys general, Chief justices, Singaporean politicians

Chan Sek Keong SPMP DUT (Second Class) DUBC SC (born 5 November 1937) is a Singaporean former judge. He served as the third Chief Justice from 2006 until his retirement in 2012. He also served as Singapore's Attorney-General from 1992 to 2006.

Chan was born in Ipoh, Perak, Malaya. His family were ethnic Chinese of a Cantonese background.

[[Mike Resnick]]

CATEGORIES: 1942 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from lymphoma, Cancer deaths in Ohio, American science fiction writers, Writers from Chicago

Michael Diamond Resnick (ˈ; March 5, 1942 – January 9, 2020) was an American science fiction writer under the name Mike Resnick. He won five Hugo Awards. He was executive editor of Jim Baen's Universe. Resnick was born in Chicago. He was best known for his novellas The Goddess of Ganymede, Stalking the Unicorn and Kirinyaga.

Resnick was diagnosed with an aggressive form of lymphoma in November 2019. He died from the disease at a hospital in Cincinnati, Ohio on January 9, 2020 at the age of 77.

[[Congress of Tucumán]]

CATEGORIES: History of South America, History of Spain

The Congress of Tucumán was a meeting in San Miguel de Tucumán where people from what is now Argentina, Uruguay, and part of Bolivia declared Independence from the Spanish Empire on 9 July 1816.

[[Butternut squash]]

CATEGORIES: Cucurbitaceae, Fruits, Vegetables, Thanksgiving

Butternut squash (Cucurbita moschata), sometimes known in Australia and New Zealand as butternut pumpkin or gramma, is a type of winter squash that grows on a vine. It has a sweet, nutty taste similar to that of a pumpkin. It has tan-yellow skin and orange fleshy pulp with a compartment of seeds in the blossom end.

[[Monarchy of Ireland]]

CATEGORIES: Ireland, History, Monarchy, United Kingdom, Northern Ireland, British royalty

Ireland is mostly the Republic of Ireland (which does not have a monarchy) and partly Northern Ireland (whose monarch is Elizabeth II). Northern Ireland is part of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland, a constitutional monarchy. Until the 20th century, all Ireland had a constitutional monarchy and was a part of the United Kingdom since 1801. Monarchies were in existence through most of the history of Ireland.

In the High Middle Ages, the Gaelic kingdoms of Ireland ended when the Normans invaded Ireland. Ireland became a fief of the Papal States (the government of the Pope). The King of England's government started to control many of the lands of Ireland. This continued until the English Reformation, when the Kingdom of England got full ownership of Ireland. The Kingdom of Ireland came into existence in the reign of Henry VIII. Henry VIII was the first to be both King of England and King of Ireland.

The Kingdom of Ireland started in 1542. Before 1603, Ireland shared a monarch with the Kingdom of England (but not with the Kingdom of Scotland) in a personal union. When Henry VIII's daughter Elizabeth I died in 1603, James VI and I became the first to be King of Ireland, King of England, and King of Scotland in a three-kingdom personal union. Between 1603 and 1707, the Kingdom of Ireland shared the monarchs of the Kingdom of Scotland and the Kingdom of England. Anne was the Queen of Ireland when the United Kingdom of Great Britain came into existence in 1707. Anne was Queen of Ireland and Queen of Great Britain. Between 1707 and 1801, the Kingdom of Ireland shared the British monarchy with the United Kingdom of Great Britain. (During the government of Oliver Cromwell, the British Isles became a republic: the Commonwealth of England, Scotland, and Ireland.) George III was King of Ireland when the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland came into existence at the start of 1801. George III was the first to be king of the new kingdom, which combined the whole British Isles (except the Isle of Man) into one kingdom for the first time.

In December 1922, most of Ireland left the United Kingdom to become part of the Irish Free State, a dominion within the British Empire; the rest, Northern Ireland, remained within the United Kingdom. In 1937, after George V died, the Free State changed its laws to give the British monarchs much less power. In April 1949, the Republic of Ireland stopped having a monarchy entirely, and left the Commonwealth of Nations. Since then, the only part of Ireland to have a monarchy is Northern Ireland (because it is part of the United Kingdom). Elizabeth II is the present queen. Charles, Prince of Wales is the heir apparent.

[[Bernt Andersson]]

CATEGORIES: Swedish footballers, Swedish football managers, 1933 births, 2020 deaths

Bernt "Sump-Hugo" Andersson (5 September 1933 – 6 January 2020) was a Swedish footballer and football manager. He made 91 Allsvenskan appearance for Djurgårdens IF and scored 19 goals. He managed Halmstads BK, Vasalunds IF and Helsingborgs IF.

Andersson died on 6 January 2020 at the age of 86.

[[Peter Renaday]]

CATEGORIES: 1935 births, Living people, American voice actors, American radio actors, American stage actors, American movie actors, American television actors, Actors from Louisiana

Pierre Laurent Renoudet (born June 9, 1935), better known as Peter Renaday, is an American actor and voice actor. He was born in New Iberia, Louisiana. 

Renaday was known for his roles in The Batman Superman Movie: World's Finest, The Lion King II: Simba's Pride, Antz (1998), The Odd Couple II (1998), Mulan (1998), The Prince of Egypt (1998), Ringmaster (1998), Scooby-Doo! and the Witch's Ghost (1999), The Road to El Dorado (2000), Shrek (2001), Madagascar (2005) and The Princess and the Frog (2009).

[[Iberia Parish, Louisiana]]

CATEGORIES: 19th-century establishments in Louisiana, 1868 establishments in the United States, Louisiana parishes

Iberia Parish (Paroisse de l'Ibérie, Parroquia de Iberia) is a parish in the U.S. state of Louisiana. As of the 2010 census, the population was 73,240. The parish seat is New Iberia.

[[Pete Dye]]

CATEGORIES: 1925 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from dementia, Disease-related deaths in Florida, American golfers, American architects, People from Ohio

Paul B. "Pete" Dye (December 29, 1925 – January 9, 2020) was an American golf course designer. He was a member of a family of course designers. He was married to fellow designer and former amateur champion Alice Dye. 

Dye designed the Radrick Farms Golf Course for the University of Michigan in 1962, but the course did not open until 1965. Dye's first well-known course was Crooked Stick Golf Club in Carmel, Indiana, north of Indianapolis, begun in 1964.

Dye died on January 9, 2020 in Gulf Stream, Florida of dementia-related problems at the age of 94.

[[Urbana, Ohio]]

CATEGORIES: Cities in Ohio, County seats in Ohio

Urbana is a city in and the county seat of Champaign County, Ohio, United States, 47 west of Columbus. The population was 11,405 in 2017. It is the home of Urbana University.

[[Champaign County, Ohio]]

CATEGORIES: 1800s establishments in Ohio, 1805 establishments in the United States, Ohio counties

Champaign County is a county located in the U.S. state of Ohio. As of the 2010 census, the population was 40,097. Its county seat is Urbana. 

[[Alice Dye]]

CATEGORIES: American golfers, 1927 births, 2019 deaths, American architects, Sportspeople from Indianapolis, Indiana

Alice Dye (February 19, 1927 – February 1, 2019) was an American amateur golfer and golf course designer. She was known as the "First Lady" of golf architecture in the United States. She was married to Pete Dye. She was born in Indianapolis, Indiana. 

She was a member of the USGA Women's Committee, the LPGA Advisory Council and a member of the Board of Directors of the Women's Western Amateur who honored her with their Woman of Distinction Award. She and her husband established a golf training program at Purdue University.

Dye died on February 1, 2019 in Gulf Stream, Florida at the age of 91.

[[Gulf Stream, Florida]]

CATEGORIES: Towns in Florida, Palm Beach County, Florida

Gulf Stream is a town in Palm Beach County, Florida, United States. The population was 716 at the 2000 census.

[[Dick Saslaw]]

CATEGORIES: 1940 births, Living people, State legislators of the United States, Politicians from Virginia, Politicians from Washington, D.C., People from Alexandria, Virginia, US Democratic Party politicians

Richard Lawrence Saslaw (born February 5, 1940) is an American politician. He is a Democrat. He was in the Virginia House of Delegates from 1976 to 1980. He was elected to the Senate of Virginia. 

Saslaw has been the leader of the Virginia Senate Democrats since 1998, and is the current Majority Leader since 2020. He was Minority Leader 1998 through 2008 and again from 2012 through 2014.

He ran for Congress in Virginia's 8th congressional district in 1984. He was defeated by then-Congressman Stanford Parris. He was born in Washington, D.C..

[[Woodlands North MRT station]]

CATEGORIES: Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore) stations

Woodlands North MRT station (TE1) is a underground Mass Rapid Transit terminal station in Woodlands, Singapore. It is  located near Republic Polytechnic. The station is the northern terminal of the Thomson–East Coast line (TEL).

A planned Johor Bahru–Singapore Rapid Transit System (RTS) at this station was delayed on 21 May 2019. This is due to Malaysia's financial situation. On 31 October 2019, Malaysia agreed to resume the RTS project at a lower cost although the project is still suspended until 30 April 2020.

[[Woodlands South MRT station]]

CATEGORIES: Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore) stations

Woodlands South MRT station (TE3) is a Mass Rapid Transit station on the Thomson–East Coast line in Woodlands, Singapore. It islocated directly under Christ Church Secondary School and near Singapore Sports School. 

The tracks between this station and Springleaf station are the longest on the Thomson–East Coast line.

The station served as a terminus of the Thomson–East Coast line from 31 January 2020 until the opening of second phase of the line on August 28, 2021. Caldecott then serve as the terminus.

[[Lawrence v. Texas]]

CATEGORIES: 2003 in Texas, LGBT in the United States, Paraphilias, United States Supreme Court cases

Lawrence v. Texas, 539 US 558 (2003), is the primary piece of case law which ultimately decriminalized sodomy in the United States. Ruled upon by the United States Supreme Court in 2003, Lawrence v. Texas concerned a Texas law that criminalized consensual, adult homosexual intercourse which was found unconstitutional under the Due Process clause of the Fourteenth Amendment.

[[2020 Republican National Convention]]

CATEGORIES: 2020 United States presidential election

The 2020 Republican National Convention was an event in which delegates of the United States Republican Party selected the party's nominees for president and vice president in the 2020 United States presidential election. 

Plans to hold a traditional large-scale convention were canceled a few weeks before the convention, due to the 2020 coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic in the United States. 

The convention was held from August 24 to 27, 2020. The convention renominated Donald Trump for president and Mike Pence for vice president.

The convention was originally scheduled to be held at the Spectrum Center in Charlotte, North Carolina, but on June 2, 2020, Trump and the Republican National Committee pulled the event from Charlotte, the North Carolina state government declined to agree to Trump's demand to allow the convention to take place with a full crowd and without public health measures to prevent the spread of the COVID-19 pandemic. Trump then announced that the convention would be moved to Jacksonville, Florida, before canceling Jacksonville convention plans on July 23. Some convention proceedings, albeit dramatically reduced in scale, were held in Charlotte. 

In August 2020, Trump said he would accept the Republican nomination live from the White House. Over 1500 gathered in front of the White House to watch. People were seated  close together, so it did not follow social distancing.

[[Smithtown, New York]]

CATEGORIES: Towns in New York

Smithtown is a town in Suffolk County, New York, United States. It is on the North Shore of Long Island. This town is an eastern suburb of New York City.

The population was 117,801 at the 2010 Census.

[[Ivan Passer]]

CATEGORIES: 1933 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from COPD, American movie directors, American screenwriters, Writers from Prague

Ivan Passer (10 July 1933 – 9 January 2020) was a Czech-American movie director and screenwriter. He was born in Prague. He studied with Miloš Forman, Václav Havel and Jerzy Skolimowski. He directed his first feature, Intimate Lighting, which was released in 1965.

Passer died on January 9, 2020 in Reno, Nevada of problems caused by chronic obstructive pulmonary disease at the age of 86.

[[The Alexander Brothers]]

CATEGORIES: 1934 births, 1935 births, 2013 deaths, 2020 deaths, Scottish musical groups, Musical duos

The Alexander Brothers were an easy-listening folk-music duo from Scotland, who had been performing since they began in the 1950s. They retired in 2012. 

The band was made up of brothers: Tom Alexander (1934–2020) and Jack Alexander (1935–2013). They were born in Thrashbush Avenue Cambusnethan, near Wishaw, Scotland.

Their biggest hit single was "Nobody's Child" in 1964. It sold more copies in Scotland that year than did recordings by The Beatles. Their other hits include "These Are My Mountains", "The Northern Lights of Old Aberdeen", "Bonnie Wee Jeannie McColl", and "Two Highland Lads".

On 2 November 2013, Jack Alexander died aged 77. On 10 January 2020, the death of Tom Alexander was announced.  He was 85.

[[John Crosbie]]

CATEGORIES: 1931 births, 2020 deaths, Canadian politicians, People from Newfoundland and Labrador, Privy Councillors (Canada), Members of the House of Commons of Canada, Canadian Queen's Counsel

John Carnell Crosbie, CAN (January 30, 1931 – January 10, 2020) was a Canadian politician. He was the 12th Lieutenant Governor of Newfoundland and Labrador from 2008 through 2013.

He worked as a federal Cabinet minister during the governments of Joe Clark and Brian Mulroney. 

Crosbie ran unsuccessfully for the leadership of the Liberal Party of Newfoundland and Labrador in 1969, losing to Smallwood, and was also a candidate in the Progressive Conservative Party of Canada's 1983 leadership election, placing third. 

Crosbie died on January 10, 2020 after a short-illness at the age of 88.

[[Werewolf (hidden role game)]]

Werewolf is a hidden role game made by Dmitry Davidoff in 1986. It is also called Mafia. The game is usually between two teams. There is an evil team that less players belong to. This group knows who is good and who is evil. They have to hide that they are evil from the good team. There is the good team, called the village, that has most of the players. People in this team have to find out who is good and bad. Everyone is given their role at the beginning of the game by a person who is not playing, called a moderator. The game has two stages, day and night. At night, everyone closes their eyes. The moderator tells the evil team to open their eyes. They choose someone to kill or remove from the game. Some other roles on both teams can do things at night. In the day, everyone opens their eyes. The players that are still alive will talk to each other about everyone's roles. They also each choose someone to kill, and the person that the most people choose will be killed. The game keeps going until only the members from one team are left.

CATEGORIES: 1993 births, Living people, English movie actors, English television actors, English stage actors, English voice actors, Actors from London, Singers from London

Naomi Grace Scott (born 6 May 1993) is an English actress and singer. She is best known for starring as Princess Jasmine in Disney's musical fantasy movie Aladdin (2019). She also starred in Power Rangers (2017) and the action comedy movie Charlie's Angels (2019).

[[Damüls]]

CATEGORIES: Cities and towns in Vorarlberg

Damüls is a municipality and popular tourism resort in Bregenz in the Austrian state of Vorarlberg. Damüls also holds the world record of the municipality with the most annual snowfall in Europe – the average is 9.30 meters per year. In 2006, Damüls was awarded the honorary title "the snowiest village in the world".

[[David Dixon Porter]]

CATEGORIES: 1813 births, 1891 deaths, Deaths from myocardial infarction, Burials at Arlington National Cemetery, American military people, People from Pennsylvania

David Dixon Porter (June 8, 1813 – February 13, 1891) was a United States Navy admiral. Porter helped improve the Navy as the Superintendent of the U.S. Naval Academy after significant service in the American Civil War.

He died at the age of 77 on the morning of February 13, 1891 of a heart attack.

Porter is interred at Arlington National Cemetery.

[[Parts per million]]

CATEGORIES: Chemical nomenclature, Units of measurement

Parts per million is a unit which expresses a small amount of dimensionless quantities. Proportionally, parts per million represents one thousandth of a millilitre of something per litre of water, or one milligram of something per kilogram of soil.

[[Hal Smith (infielder)]]

CATEGORIES: 1930 births, 2020 deaths, Baltimore Orioles players, Cincinnati Reds players, Houston Astros players, Pittsburgh Pirates players, Kansas City Athletics players, Sportspeople from Illinois

Harold Wayne Smith (December 7, 1930 – January 9, 2020) was an American professional baseball player. He played in Major League Baseball from 1955 to 1964. He played for five different teams. During the 1960 World Series, he was a member of the Pittsburgh Pirates. 

Smith died on January 9, 2020 in Columbus, Texas at the age 89.

[[Guido Messina]]

CATEGORIES: 1931 births, 2020 deaths, Italian cyclists, Italian Olympians, Olympic gold medalists

Guido Messina (4 January 1931 – 10 January 2020) was an Italian road and track cyclist. He won a gold medal with the Italian team at the 1952 Olympics. Between 1954 and 1963 he rode professionally and won the first stage of the 1955 Giro d'Italia. He was born in Monreale, Italy.

Messina died on 10 January 2020 in Torino, Italy at the age of 89.

[[Kufstein District]]

CATEGORIES: Districts of Tyrol (state)

The Kufstein District is a district in Tyrol, Austria. It borders Bavaria (Germany) in the north, the Kitzbühel district in the southeast, and the Schwaz district in the southwest. It has an area of 969.81 km². As of 2012, 101,321 people lived there. The administrative center is Kufstein.

The district has the lower part of the Tyrolean Inn valley as far as the Bavarian border, the Alpbach valley, the Brandenberg valley, Wildschönau, and Thiersee. Mountain ranges within the district include the Brandenberg Alps, Kitzbühel Alps, and the Kaisergebirge. The largest lakes are the Reintal lakes, Thiersee, Hechtsee, Hintersteiner See and Walchsee.

CATEGORIES: 1969 births, English voice actors, English comedians, English television presenters, People from Westminster, Actors from London, Living people

Dave Lamb (born 17 January 1969), instead of David Alexander Lamb or David Lamb, is an English comedian, television presenter and voice actor. He is best known for presenting Come Dine with Me, Goodness Gracious Me and Horrible Histories: Gory Games.

[[Landeck District]]

CATEGORIES: Districts of Tyrol (state)

The Landeck District (Distretto di Landeck) is a in Tyrol, Austria. It is next to Reutte to the north, Imst to the east, South Tyrol (Italy) and Graubünden (Switzerland) to the south, and Bludenz (Vorarlberg) to the west.

Its area is 1,595 km². As of 2015, 43,886 people lived there. The administrative center is Landeck.

[[Galen Cole]]

CATEGORIES: People from Bangor, Maine, 1925 births, 2020 deaths, Businesspeople from Maine, American military personnel of World War II, American philanthropists

Galen Cole (November 29, 1925 – January 9, 2020) was an American military personnel of World War II and philanthropist. He was born in Bangor, Maine, Cole managed the Cole Land Transportation Museum and the Walking Sticks for Veterans program. He organized many activities and charity drives for veterans and related causes in Bangor. He was part of the United States Marines and was a Purple Heart recipient.

Cole died on January 9, 2020 in Bangor at the age of 94.

[[Wolfgang Dauner]]

CATEGORIES: 1935 births, 2020 deaths, German composers, German pianists, Jazz musicians, People from Stuttgart

Wolfgang Dauner (30 December 1935 – 10 January 2020) was a German jazz fusion pianist. He worked in the United Jazz and Rock Ensemble and with Hans Koller, Albert Mangelsdorff, Volker Kriegel and Ack van Rooyen. In 1969, he was leader and composer for Radio Jazz Group Stuttgart. A year later he started the jazz rock band Et Cetera.

Dauner died on 10 January 2020 in Stuttgart, Germany at the age of 84.

[[Bildungsroman]]

CATEGORIES: Genres

A Bildungsroman is a kind of novel. It is often called a "coming-of-age" story in English. The word comes from German. "Bildung" means "education", and "Roman", means "novel."  This genre is about the psychological and moral growth of the main character from youth to adulthood.  The ways the character changes are important.

"The Day Before the Revolution" is a  science fiction short story by American writer Ursula K. Le Guin, first published in 1974.

It is a short story that happens before the story in the novel The Dispossessed. The main character is "Odo". She is the woman who led the revolution that started the anarchist society in The Dispossessed.

[[PJ Masks]]

CATEGORIES: Television series by Disney, Animated television series, 2015 establishments, English-language television programs

The PJ Masks is an animated children's television series. It began on the Disney Junior on September 18, 2015, on France 5 on 18 December 2015 and on the Disney Junior in Canada on February 7, 2016. The series is based on the Les Pyjamasques book series by Romuald Racioppo.

Three 6 year old kids, Amaya, Connor and Greg become the fictional characters Owlette (an owl), Catboy (a cat) and Gekko (a lizard), or the PJ Masks. Together, the characters save the day and seldom lose.

The villains of the show include Night Ninja, Romeo and Luna Girl.

[[Xavier Riddle and the Secret Museum]]

[[Qaboos bin Said]]

CATEGORIES: 1940 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from colorectal cancer, Sultans of Oman

Qaboos bin Said Al Said (قابوس بن سعيد آل سعيد‎; 18 November 1940 – 10 January 2020) was the Sultan of Oman from 1970 until his death in 2020. He was a fourteenth-generation descendant of the founder of the House of Al Said. He was the longest-serving leader in the Middle East and Arab world, serving for almost fifty years.

Qaboos died of colon cancer on 10 January 2020 in Muscat. He was 79. After he died, Haitham bin Tariq Al Said became the Sultan of Oman.

[[S4C]]

CATEGORIES: 1982 establishments in the United Kingdom, British television channels

S4C (ˌɛs ˌpɛdwar ˈɛk, from the Welsh Sianel Pedwar Cymru, meaning Channel Four Wales) is a Welsh-language free-to-air television channel. It first started in 1982 in Wales only, as the fourth analogue channel (after BBC One, ITV, and BBC Two). It was the first Welsh-language television channel, and still is. 

The rest of the United Kingdom had Channel 4 instead. S4C did also show some Channel 4 programmes in English at first, but both channels can now be watched in Wales.  S4C can be watched in all of the United Kingdom on Freeview and other services since 2010.

[[Central India]]

CATEGORIES: Regions of India

Central India is an Indian region.

Central India consists of two Indian states: Madhya Pradesh and Chhattisgarh. It shares a border with  Rajasthan, Gujarat, Odisha, Jharkhand, Uttar Pradesh, Maharashtra and Telangana.One of the states i.e.Chattisgarh is ruled by the Congress with Chief Minister Bhupesh Baghel.

This map of India (press to open) shows all central Indian states in the color pink. The larger one is Madhya Pradesh while the smaller one is Chhattisgarh.

[[Petko Petkov (footballer)]]

CATEGORIES: 1946 births, 2020 deaths, Bulgarian footballers, Bulgarian football managers

Petko Petkov (Петко Петков; 3 August 1946 – 10 January 2020) was a Bulgarian football player and manager. He played as a forward.

Petkov was born in Sinitevo. He played club football for many teams including Beroe Stara Zagora and Austria Wien. He is Beroe Stara Zagora's record goalscorer in the top league with 144 goals in 260 matches. He also played for the Bulgaria national team. He played 33 times for his country, scoring five goals.

On 10 January 2020, Petkov died in Stara Zagora at the age of 73.

[[Scene (British TV series)]]

CATEGORIES: British drama television series, 1960s British television series, 1970s British television series, 1980s British television series, 1990s British television series, 2000s British television series

Scene is a British television anthology drama/documentary series. It was made by the BBC for teenagers. It had plays on current issues and some documentaries. The plays were by leading contemporary playwrights. Playwrights included Willy Russell, Fay Weldon, Tom Stoppard, Alan Plater, Al Hunter Ashton. They were first broadcast to a school audience as part of BBC Schools. Dramas from the series were also broadcast for a wider adult audience. The series ran from 1968 to 2002. Some of the dramas received awards.

Scene was a series of 30 minute dramas and documentaries suitable for showing to teenage schoolchildren as part of the English and Humanities curriculum. It was thought that the dramas shown would stimulate discussion in the classroom about contemporary issues relevant to teenagers. This included topics such as race, drugs, sex, and disability. Critical reaction was positive with praise for the high production standards.

Some of the actors featured in Scene became successful. for example: Jemima Rooper (Junk, 1999), Sarah Jane Potts, Jack Deam, Lucy Davis (Alison, 1996), Adrian Lester (Teaching Matthew, 1993), Sean Maguire (A Man of Letters, 1994), Peter Howitt (Stone Cold).

[[Reutte District]]

CATEGORIES: Districts of Tyrol (state)

The Reutte District is a district in Tyrol, Austria. It borders Bavaria (Germany) in the north, the districts Imst and Landeck in the south, and Bregenz and Bludenz (both Vorarlberg) in the west. The district is also referred to as “Außerfern”.

It has an area of is 1,236.37 km². As of 2012, 31,758 people lived there. The administrative center is Reutte.

[[Lienz District]]

CATEGORIES: Districts of Tyrol (state)

The Lienz District (Distretto di Lienz) is a district in Tyrol, Austria. It is the only district in East Tyrol. The district borders the Pinzgau (Salzburg) in the north, the districts Spittal an der Drau and Hermagor (both Carinthia) in the east, Veneto (Italy) in the south, and South Tyrol (Italy) in the west.

It has an area of 2,016.41 km². As of 2019, 48,753 people lived there. The administrative center of the district is Lienz.

[[Schwaz District]]

CATEGORIES: Districts of Tyrol (state)

The Schwaz District is a district in Tyrol, Austria. It borders Bavaria (Germany) in the north, the districts of Kufstein, Kitzbühel and Pinzgau (Salzburg) in the east, South Tyrol (Italy) in the south, and the Innsbruck-Land district in the west.

It has an area of 1,887.49 km². As of 2019, 83,873 people lived there. The administrative center of the district is Schwaz.

[[Kufstein]]

CATEGORIES: Cities and towns in Tyrol (state)

Kufstein is a town in the Austrian state of Tyrol. The town is the capital of the Kufstein District. It has about 18,400 people lived there that makes it the second largest Tyrolean town, after the state capital Innsbruck.

The greatest landmark is Kufstein Fortress, first mentioned in the 13th century.

[[Imst District]]

CATEGORIES: Districts of Tyrol (state)

The Imst District is a district in Tyrol, Austria. It borders the district Reutte in the north, as well as sharing a small border with Bavaria (Germany). It borders the district Innsbruck-Land in the east, South Tyrol (Italy) in the south, and the district Landeck in the west.

The district has an area of 1724.65, which makes it by area rank 4 of the districts of Tyrol. As of 2019, 60,056 people lived there. The administrative center of the district is Imst.

[[Reutte]]

CATEGORIES: Cities and towns in Tyrol (state)

Reutte is a market town in the Austrian state of Tyrol and is the administrative center of the Reutte District. As of 2019, 6,772 people lived there.

Reutte is on the river Lech.

[[Rudolf de Korte]]

CATEGORIES: 1936 births, 2020 deaths, Deputy Prime Ministers of the Netherlands, Dutch businesspeople, People's Party for Freedom and Democracy politicians, Politicians from The Hague

Rudolf Willem de Korte (8 July 1936 – 9 January 2020) was a Dutch politician and businessman. He was a member of the People's Party for Freedom and Democracy (VVD). He served as the leader of the VDD in 1986. He was a member of the House of Representatives (1977–1986, 1986, 1989–1995). He held many government roles, including as Deputy Prime Minister (1986–1989), Minister of Economic Affairs (1986–1989) and Minister of the Interior (1986).

De Korte was born in The Hague. He married his wife, Karin, in 1966. The couple had two children.

De Korte died on 9 January 2020 in Wassenaar, South Holland. He was 83.

[[Neda Arnerić]]

CATEGORIES: 1953 births, 2020 deaths, Movie actors, Serbian actors, Serbian politicians, Television actors

Neda Arnerić (Неда Арнерић; 15 July 1953 – 10 January 2020) was a Serbian actress and politician. She was born in Knjaževac. She was known as a sex symbol of Yugoslav cinema. She appeared in movies such as Venom (1971), Shaft in Africa (1973) and The End of the War (1984). From 2000 to 2004, she was a member of the National Assembly.

Arnerić was married to Milorad Mešterović from 1981 until his death in 2020. On 10 January 2020, Arnerić was found dead in Belgrade. She was 66.

[[Portuguese Colonial War]]

CATEGORIES: History of Angola, Wars involving Portugal

Angola:

Portuguese Guinea:

Mozambique:

Portuguese Guinea:

Mozambique:

+30,000 in Angola

The Portuguese Colonial War (Portuguese: Guerra Colonial Portuguesa) was fought between Portugal's military and the emerging nationalist movements in Portugal's African colonies between 1961 and 1974. Portugal fought the MPLA, FNLA, UNITA and FLEC in Angola between 1961 and 1974. Also, they fought the PAIGC in Guinea-Bissau between 1963 and 1974. Lastly, they fought the FRELIMO in Mozambique between 1964 and 1974.

[[Abderrazak Rassaa]]

CATEGORIES: 2020 deaths, 1930 births, People from Tunis, Tunisian politicians

Abderrazak Rassaa (عبد الرزاق  الرصاع‎; 4 January 1930 – 7 January 2020) was a Tunisian politician. He was born in Tunis. He was a member of the Socialist Destourian Party. He served as Minister of Finance from 1969 to 1971. He was also Minister of Industry from 1968 to 1969.

Rassaa died on 7 January 2020, at the age of 90.

[[Midsommar]]

CATEGORIES: 2019 horror movies, American horror movies, Hungarian movies, Swedish movies

Midsommar is a 2019 folk horror movie written and directed by Ari Aster. The movie stars Florence Pugh, Jack Reynor, William Jackson Harper, Vilhelm Blomgren, and Will Poulter. It follows a group of friends who travel to Sweden for a midsummmer festival that occurs once every ninety years and find themselves in the clutches of a dangerous pagan cult.

[[Oliver Batali Albino]]

CATEGORIES: 1935 births, 2020 deaths, African politicians, African writers, Civil servants, Deaths from heart failure, South Sudanese people

Oliver Batali Albino (11 November 1935 – 4 January 2020) was a South Sudanese politician, civil servant and writer. He was born in Yei. He served as Minister of Housing and Public Utilities from 1975 to 1978 and as Minister of Labour in 1985. In July 2011, he became a member of South Sudan's Council of States.

On 4 January 2020, Albino died of heart failure in Augusta, Georgia, United States. He was 84.

[[Florence Pugh]]

CATEGORIES: English movie actors, English television actors, 1996 births, Living people, People from Oxford

Florence Pugh (born January 3, 1996) is an English actress. She made her professional acting debut in the mystery film The Falling (2014) and gained recognition for her portrayal of an unhappily married woman in the independent drama Lady Macbeth (2016). Her performance in the latter film won her the British Independent Film Award for Best Actress.

Pugh's breakthrough came in 2019, during which she received positive reviews for her portrayals of professional wrestler Paige in the biographical sports film Fighting with My Family, an emotionally troubled woman in the horror film Midsommar, and Amy March in the coming-of-age film Little Women. For the lattermost, she received a BAFTA Award nomination for Best Actress in a Supporting Role.

[[Log driving]]

[[Valdir Joaquim de Moraes]]

CATEGORIES: 1931 births, 2020 deaths, Brazilian association football goalkeepers, Brazilian football managers, Deaths from multiple organ failure, People from Porto Alegre

Valdir Joaquim de Moraes (23 November 1931 – 11 January 2020) was a Brazilian football player and manager. He played as a goalkeeper.

De Moraes was born in Porto Alegre, Rio Grande do Sul. From 1958 to 1969, he played for Palmeiras and won many honours. He also played for the Brazil national team five times between 1956 and 1965.

De Moraes died of multiple organ failure on 11 January 2020 in Porto Alegre. He was 88.

[[Charge of the Light Brigade]]

CATEGORIES: 1854, Battles involving France, Battles involving Russia, Battles involving the United Kingdom, Idioms

The Charge of the Light Brigade was a failed military attack during the Crimean War in 1854.  It was a charge by British Light Cavalry (who didn't have many weapons or armour) against Russians and their allies.  The cavalry were supposed to attack regular soldiers, which they were good at, but the British leaders made a mistake and caused the cavalry to attack artillery guns, which they were not good at.  It is remembered because there was a poem written by Alfred, Lord Tennyson that praised the bravery of the soldiers. It was also seen as a symbol of the failures of British rulers during that time.

[[Fram]]

Fram ("Forward") is a ship that was used in expeditions of the Arctic and Antarctic regions by the Norwegian explorers Fridtjof Nansen, Otto Sverdrup, Oscar Wisting, and Roald Amundsen between 1893 and 1912. It was designed and built by the Scottish-Norwegian shipwright Colin Archer for Fridtjof Nansen's 1893 Arctic expedition in which the plan was to freeze Fram into the Arctic ice sheet and float with it over the North Pole.

[[Nuthatch]]

CATEGORIES: Passeri

The nuthatches are  Sitta, a genus of small passerine birds in the family Sittidae. They live in the Northern Hemisphere.

They have large heads, short tails, and powerful bills and feet. Nuthatches advertise their territory with loud, simple songs. Most species have grey or bluish upperparts and a black eye stripe.

They live in forests, often pine coniferous forests, on higher land (montane forests). As usual in such places, insects, nuts and seeds are their food.

Nuthatches use holes in trees for nests. This means they compete with squirrels and woodpeckers for these holes. In fact both squirrels and the great spotted woodpecker kill nuthatches if they can. Owls and hawks also kill these small birds, but that is not to do with their nest-holes. In defence of their nests, nuthatches make the entrances smaller by packing the edges with mud or tree resin. Predation is not really a threat, just a fact of life for them. Loss of coniferous forest in some countries is a threat. They cannot live except in trees.

All nuthatches store food, especially seeds. They hide seeds in tree crevices, in the ground, under small stones, or behind bark flakes.  These stores are remembered for as long as 30 days.

[[Steyr]]

CATEGORIES: Cities and towns in Upper Austria, Districts of Upper Austria

Steyr is a city in the Austrian state of Upper Austria. It is the capital, though not part of Steyr-Land District. Steyr is Austria's 12th most populated city and the third largest city in Upper Austria. As of 1 January 2019, it has about 38,100 people living there.

The city is in the Traunviertel region, with the two rivers Steyr and Enns flowing through it.

[[La Parka II]]

CATEGORIES: 1966 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from multiple organ failure, Deaths from renal failure, Deaths from respiratory failure, Mexican professional wrestlers

Jesús Alfonso Huerta Escoboza (4 January 1966 – 11 January 2020), better known as La Parka or La Parka II, was a Mexican masked professional wrestler (luchador enmascarado). He worked for the professional wrestling promotion AAA from the mid-1990s until 2019. He was born in Hermosillo, Sonora.

Escoboza was not the first wrestler to use the ring name "La Parka". Adolfo Tapia was the first "La Parka" but did not own the trademark or copyright on the name or the character. In the late 1990s, Escoboza was billed as "La Parka Jr.". In 2003, he became the "official" La Parka. Tapia was forced to stop using the name and instead became known as L.A. Park.

Escoboza was badly injured in an October 2019 wrestling match. On 11 January 2020, he died of lung and kidney failure as a result of his injuries. He was 54.

[[Philo of Alexandria]]

CATEGORIES: 1st century BC births, 1st century deaths, Egyptian Jews, Jewish philosophers, People from Alexandria

Philo Judaeus, also known as Philo of Alexandria, was a Jewish philosopher who lived from c. 20 BC to c. 50 AD. Philo wanted to prove that the Torah and Greek philosophy actually agreed with each other and he used allegory to do that. In 38 AD, Philo was one of many Egyptian Jews to meet with the Roman Emperor Caligula and he wrote a book about it.

[[In Another World with My Smartphone]]

CATEGORIES: Light novels

In Another World with My Smartphone is a Japanese light novel series. It is written by Patora Fuyuhara and the pictures are drawn by Eiji Usatsuka. It started being published online in 2013 on Shōsetsuka ni Narō. Hobby Japan later started publishing it as Light Novels. The English version of the series is released by J-Novel Club. A manga based on this light novel by Soto began publishing in Kadokawa Shoten's Comp Ace in November 2016. An anime television series by Production Reed aired from July to September 2017. The series has been licensed by Crunchyroll.

The series is popular on the Shōsetsuka ni Narō website. It has been viewed over 100,000,000 times in total.

[[Jayalath Manoratne]]

CATEGORIES: 1948 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from brain cancer, Sri Lankan movie actors, Sri Lankan people, Stage actors, Television actors

Keselgaspe Manatunga Jayalath Manoratne (කෙසෙල්ගස්පේ මනතුංග ජයලත් මනෝරත්න; 12 June 1948 – 12 January 2020) was a Sri Lankan actor. He appeared in movies, television and on stage. He had roles in Doo Daruwo, Handaya and Hiripoda Wassa. He was born in Nuwara Eliya.

Manoratne died of brain cancer on 12 January 2020 in Maharagama, Colombo. He was 71.

[[Walter J. Boyne]]

CATEGORIES: 1929 births, 2020 deaths, American aviators, American military people, Writers from St. Louis, Missouri, United States Air Force

Walter J. Boyne (February 2, 1929 – January 9, 2020) was an American USAF officer, command pilot, combat veteran, aviation historian and author. He wrote more than 50 books and over 1,000 magazine articles. While most of his books were non-fiction, Boyne wrote some works of fiction, including The Wild Blue: The Novel of the U.S. Air Force (1986). Boyne served as director of the National Air and Space Museum at the Smithsonian Institution. He was also chairman of the National Aeronautic Association.

Boyne was born in East St. Louis, Illinois. He was married to Jeanne Quigley until her death in 2007. The couple had four children. In 2008, he married Terezia Takacs.

Boyne died on January 9, 2020 in Silver Spring, Maryland. He was 90.

[[Aart Staartjes]]

CATEGORIES: 1938 births, 2020 deaths, Dutch television actors, Dutch television presenters, Road accident deaths, People from Amsterdam

Aart Staartjes (1 March 1938 – 12 January 2020) was a Dutch actor, director, television presenter and documentary maker. He was born in Nieuwendam, Amsterdam. He is best known for his role as Meneer Aart on Sesamstraat, the Dutch co-production of Sesame Street. Staartjes also presented the yearly arrival of Sinterklaas in the Netherlands.

On 10 January 2020, Staartjes was injured in a car accident. Two days later, he died of his injuries in Groningen. He was 81.

[[Paulo Gonçalves (motorcyclist)]]

CATEGORIES: 1979 births, 2020 deaths, Accidental deaths, Deaths in sport, Portuguese sportspeople

Paulo Gonçalves (5 February 1979 – 12 January 2020) was a Portuguese rally racing motorcycle rider. He was born in Gemeses, Esposende. He notably won the FIM Cross-Country Rallies World Championship in 2013. At the time of his death in 2020, his team was Hero MotoCorp. He was also a member of KTM, Honda and Husqvarna Motorcycles

On 12 January 2020, Gonçalves crashed during the seventh stage of the Dakar Rally in Saudi Arabia. He was taken to a hospital in the town of Layla where he was pronounced dead. He was 40.

Paulo Gonçalves (born 18 November 1936) is a Brazilian football manager.

Gonçalves was the head coach of the Brazil women's national team at the 2003 FIFA Women's World Cup.
