Khatib MRT station (NS14) is an  Mass Rapid Transit (MRT) station on the North South line in Yishun, Singapore.

The section of tracks between this station and Yio Chu Kang MRT station is the longest between any two stations on the North South line.

Davies was born in St Asaph, Flintshire, Wales. He grew up in Wem, Shropshire, England. Davies is noted for his height, standing 6 tall. 

[[Nikolai Tsymbal]]

CATEGORIES: 1925 births, 2020 deaths, Soviet military personnel of World War II, Soviet generals, Russian generals

Nikolai Andreyevich Tsymbal (Николай Андреевич Цымбал; 20 January 1925 – 15 January 2020) was an officer of the Soviet Armed Forces. He worked in the force's political branch and reached the rank of General-Lieutenant of Aviation. He was deputy head of the Gagarin Air Force Academy. He was awarded the Order of the Red Banner, the Order of the Red Banner of Labour, and the Order of Friendship.

[[Bobby Kay]]

Romeo Cormier (5 January 1950 – 17 January 2020) was a Canadian professional wrestler. He was best known by the ring name Bobby Kay. He was a member of the Cormier wrestling family, a group of four brothers who were all successful professional wrestlers. 

He worked in Canada and the United States from 1967 to the mid-1980s. He owned and operated part of the Eastern Sports Association. After retiring from wrestling, he performed country music professionally before taking a job with Loblaws.

[[Mark Pocan]]

From 1999 to 2013 he was a member of the Wisconsin State Assembly. 

He is openly gay.

[[Peroxisome]]

CATEGORIES: Cell biology

Peroxisomes or microbodies are organelles inside eukariotic cells which are enclosed  with a membrane. They are involved in various processes, and use up oxygen.

Peroxisomes play an important role in  metabolism, reactive oxygen species detoxification, and signaling.

[[Al-Nabk District]]

Al-Nabk is a town in Syria. It is located to the North of Damascus, the capital. It takes about 90 minutes by car from the main international Airport. The population is about forty thousand people. The weather is very cold and snowy in winter because Al-Nabk lies on high mountains. It is about 1360 meter above the sea level. However, in summer the weather is very nice and warm. It is a place for spending happy holidays.

[[Gary Ablett]]

CATEGORIES: 1965 births, 2012 deaths, Cancer deaths in England, Deaths from non-Hodgkin lymphoma, English footballers, English football managers, Liverpool F.C. players, Sportspeople from Liverpool

Gareth Ian Ablett (19 November 1965 – 1 January 2012) was an English professional footballer and manager. He played as a defender. His professional career lasted from 1985 until 2001.

Ablett was born in the Liverpool suburb of Aigburth. He played for Liverpool between 1985 and 1992. With the club, he won two league titles and an FA Cup, winning against Everton in the 1989 final. In 1995, Ablett moved from Liverpool to city rivals Everton. Later that year, he won the FA Cup with Everton. He remains the only played to win an FA Cup with both clubs. He also played for Derby County, Hull City, Sheffield United, Birmingham City, Wycombe Wanderers, Blackpool and the Long Island Rough Riders during his career. He was also a youth team manager for Liverpool and Everton. From 2009 to 2010, he was manager of Stockport County.

On 1 January 2012, Ablett died of non-Hodgkin lymphoma in Tarleton, Lancashire. He was 46.

[[Fiestas de San Blas y Santa Águeda (Mequinenza)]]

CATEGORIES: Parties

Fiestas de San Blas and Santa Águeda is a celebration of the municipality of Mequinenza in the province of Zaragoza, an autonomous community of Aragon that consists of a holiday that is part of the historical tradition of the town due to its age and continuity through time and for the originality and diversity of its acts, becoming a tourist phenomenon with great attraction of visitors. There is evidence of more than 300 years of celebration, with an active participation of the local population in both religious and festive celebrations. These parties include unique events such as the delivery of the baton, costume contests (both children and adults) as well as the elaboration of "coca" and "pa beneït". They take place during the first half of February, they are considered as the winter celebrations of the town and since 2018 they have been recognized as a Festival of Tourist Interest in Aragon.

[[Robert Maclennan, Baron Maclennan of Rogart]]

CATEGORIES: 1936 births, 2020 deaths, Alumni of the University of Cambridge, Alumni of the University of Oxford, Columbia University alumni, Former Labour MPs (UK), Former Liberal Democrats MPs (UK), Former members of the British House of Commons for Scottish constituencies, Leaders of the Liberal Democrats (UK), Leaders of the Social Democratic Party (UK), Members of the House of Lords, Politicians from Glasgow, Privy Councillors (UK), Social Democratic Party MPs (UK), UK MPs 1966–1970, UK MPs 1970–1974, UK MPs 1974, UK MPs 1974–1979, UK MPs 1979–1983, UK MPs 1983–1987, UK MPs 1987–1992, UK MPs 1992–1997, UK MPs 1997–2001

Robert Adam Ross Maclennan, Baron Maclennan of Rogart GBR (26 June 1936 – 18 January 2020) was a British politician and life peer. He was the last leader of the Social Democratic Party (SDP) from 1987 to 1988. He was the president of the Liberal Democrats from 1995 to 1998. He served as a Member of Parliament (MP) from 1966 to 2001, when he was raised to the House of Lords.

Maclennan was born in Glasgow. His father was Sir Hector MacLennan. He died in January 2020, at the age of 83.

[[Deaths in February 2020]]

CATEGORIES: 2020 deaths, February 2020 events

The following is a list of deaths that should be noted in February 2020. For deaths that should be noted before the month that the world is in, please see "Months". Names under each date are noted in the order of the alphabet by last name or pseudonym. Deaths of non-humans are noted here also if it is worth noting.

Each listing of a death must have a source. If no reference is included, the death notice will be removed. The following are the requirements of adding a name to the list in its order: name, age, where they came from, what the person is known for, cause of death (if known) and a source.

[[James Mollison]]

CATEGORIES: 1931 births, 2020 deaths, Australian businesspeople, Order of Australia, People from Victoria (Australia)

James Mollison AUS (20 March 1931 – 19 January 2020) was an Australian arts administrator. He was acting director of the National Gallery of Australia (NGA) from 1971 to 1977 and director from 1977 to 1990. He was also director of the National Gallery of Victoria from 1989 to 1995. He was born in Wonthaggi, Victoria.

Mollison retired as the NGA's director in 1990 and moved to Melbourne to become director of the National Gallery of Victoria. He died on 19 January 2020, at the age of 88.

[[Dick Scott (historian)]]

CATEGORIES: 1923 births, 2020 deaths, Autobiographers, Historians, New Zealand journalists, People from North Island, Officers of the New Zealand Order of Merit

Richard George Scott NZL (17 November 1923 – 1 January 2020) was a New Zealand historian and journalist. He wrote many books on the history of New Zealand. His first book, 151 Days (1952), was about the 1951 New Zealand waterfront dispute. His most well-known work is Ask That Mountain (1975), which tells the events of the non-violent Māori resistance to European occupation in Parihaka. Former New Zealand Prime Minister Helen Clark called it "one of New Zealand's most influential books." His autobiography, Dick Scott: A Radical Writer's Life, was published in 2004.

Scott was born in Palmerston North. He was the father of writer Rosie Scott (1948–2017).

Scott died on 1 January 2020, at the age of 96.

[[John N. Brandenburg]]

CATEGORIES: 1929 births, 2020 deaths, American generals, American military personnel of the Vietnam War, People from Enid, Oklahoma

John Nelson Brandenburg (April 29, 1929 – January 14, 2020) was an American lieutenant general in the U.S. Army. He was born in Enid, Oklahoma. He was a commander of the I Corps at Fort Lewis, a post which he served from 1981 to 1984. He was also a commander of the 101st Airborne Division from 1978 to 1980. He retired from the military in May 1984 after 33 years of service.

On January 14, 2020, Brandenburg died at his home in Canton, Georgia. He was 90.

[[Palmerston North]]

Palmerston North is a city in the North Island of New Zealand. It is the seat of the Manawatū-Whanganui region. The city is 140 north of the capital, Wellington. Palmerston North is the country's seventh-largest city. As of June 2018, the city had an urban population of 86,600.

[[This Morning]]

The longest serving presenter of the show is Ruth Langsford, who presented the series continously 21 years since 1999. The show orginally presented by husband and wife duo Richard Madeley and Judy Finnigan for more than a decade after its launch. It is currently presented by Phillip Schofield and Holly Willoughby to Monday to Thursday, and Dermot O'Leary and Alison Hammond on Fridays and Bank Holidays. During all school holidays including the 6 week Summer Holiday, the show is presented by Eamonn Holmes and Ruth Langsford, five days a week, while all other presenters are absent.

[[Jimmy Heath]]

CATEGORIES: 1926 births, 2020 deaths, African American musicians, American jazz musicians, American saxophonists, Deaths from natural causes, Musicians from Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, Musicians from Queens

James Edward Heath (October 25, 1926 – January 19, 2020), nicknamed "Little Bird", was an American jazz saxophonist, composer, arranger and big band leader. He was the brother of bassist Percy Heath and drummer Albert Heath. In 1975, the brothers formed the Heath Brothers. He worked with notable musicians such as John Coltrane, Stanley Cowell, Benny Golson, Specs Wright, Cal Massey, Johnny Coles, Ray Bryant, Nelson Boyd, Miles Davis, Kenny Dorham, Gil Evans, Milt Jackson, Nancy Wilson, Gerald Wilson and Art Farmer. Heath was nominated for three Grammy Awards.

Heath was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. He was the father of musician James Mtume.

On January 19, 2020, Heath died of natural causes in Loganville, Georgia. He was 93.

In 1975, the brothers formed the Heath Brothers. He notably worked with musicians such as John Coltrane, J. J. Johnson, Wes Montgomery, Art Farmer and Benny Golson's Jazztet, Cedar Walton, Bobby Timmons, Kenny Drew, Sonny Rollins, Dexter Gordon, Johnny Griffin, Herbie Hancock, Friedrich Gulda, Nina Simone and Yusef Lateef.

[[Minié ball]]

CATEGORIES: Weapons

The Minié ball, or Minni ball, is a type of muzzle-loading spin-stabilized bullet for rifled muskets named after its developer, Claude-Étienne Minié, inventor of the French Minié rifle. It came to prominence in the Crimean War and American Civil War.

Rifling, the addition of spiral grooves inside a gun barrel, givesa spin to a bullet, greatly increasing the range and accuracy of a gun. Before the Minié ball, balls had to be jammed down the rifle barrel, sometimes with a mallet, and after a relatively small number of shots, gunpowder leftovers built up in the spiral grooves, which then had to be cleaned out. The development of the Minié ball was significant, because it was the first projectile that was small enough to be easily put down the barrel of a rifled long gun. Both the American Springfield Model 1861 and the British Pattern 1853 Enfield rifled muskets, the most common weapons used during the American Civil War, used the Minié ball.

The Minié ball did a lot if damage in the American Civil War. It made it really hard for surgeons to treat wounded soldiers because Minié balls shattered bones often.

[[Rhona and Rhoda Wurtele]]

CATEGORIES: 1922 births, 2020 deaths, Living people, 1952 Winter Olympics, Canadian Olympians, Order of Canada, Sibling duos, Sportspeople from Quebec, Twin people from Canada

Grace Rhona Wurtele Gillis CAN (January 21, 1922 – January 17, 2020) and Isabella Rhoda Wurtele Eaves CAN (born January 21, 1922) were Canadian skiers. They were identical twin sisters. The pair were active in the 1940s and 1950s. The duo won many North American skiing competitions. Together they made up the entire 1948 Winter Olympics women's alpine team for Canada. Rhoda also competed at the 1952 Winter Olympics. The Wurteles were born in Saint-Lambert, Quebec.

[[Crossroads (British TV series)]]

CATEGORIES: 2003 British television series endings

Crossroads (later known as Crossroads Motel) is  a British television soap opera. It was shown on ITV. It began in 1964 and finished in 1988. There was a revival from 2001 to 2003.

Crossroads was set in a fictional motel in the Midlands. Crossroads was later called a hotel. The show became a byword for cheap production values. Despite this, the series regularly attracted huge audiences. It had as many as 15 million viewers.

It was created by Hazel Adair and Peter Ling and produced by ATV. In 1981, Central Independent Television took over ATV's broadcast licence and continued the programme until it was cancelled in 1988. In 2001, the series was revived by Carlton Television. It was cancelled again in 2003.

[[List of Crossroads characters]]

CATEGORIES: ITV

The British television soap opera Crossroads had its original run from 1964 to 1988. The only character in all twenty-four years was  Jill Richardson, played by Jane Rossington.

[[The Brian May Band]]

CATEGORIES: American rock bands, English rock bands, 1991 establishments

The Brian May Band was an English-American rock band formed by Queen guitarist Brian May. The band was originally formed in October 1991 for May's performance at Guitar Legends guitar festival in Seville, Spain. They toured with May to promote some of his studio albums.

The rhythm section for the band was Cozy Powell and Neil Murray, who had already worked together in Black Sabbath and Whitesnake. Spike Edney, who was the tour keyboardist for Queen between 1984 and 1986 took the keyboard spot.

The band soon went on a tour of the United States, Europe and Japan. The tour ended in December 1993, when May returned to the studio with fellow Queen band mates Roger Taylor and John Deacon for Queen's final studio album, Made In Heaven. Meanwhile, Cozy Powell and Neil Murray returned to work with Black Sabbath, and both later joined Peter Green's Band.

The band reunited in 1998 to promote Brian May's Another World album. Eric Singer, of later KISS fame, was brought as the last minute replacement for Cozy Powell, who had died in a car accident earlier that year.

In 2005, both Jamie Moses and Spike Edney joined the Queen + Paul Rodgers collaboration on their worldwide tour.

Their only release was the live album, Live at the Brixton Academy in 1993.

She is best known for establishing the first constitutional court in the Dominican Republic and founding a drone based logistics company, Matternet that first drone delivery platform authorized for permanent operations in any city. Santana has also founded Social Glass, a software product for the government system.

[[Gross indecency]]

CATEGORIES: Law

Gross indecency is a legal term used in some English-speaking countries. It was first used to criminalize sexual acts between men, in 1855. Oscar Wilde was charged with gross indecency, in 1895. Alan Turing also pleaded guilty to the charge of gross indecency. If two men either have oral or anal sex, this is called sodomy. It is punished differently, in places where it is a crime.

[[Realism theory]]

CATEGORIES: International relations, Political philosophy

Realism theory is a way of thinking about politics and world history, that focuses on being realistic. It is one of the main styles of international relations theory. It gives the theoretic background to Realpolitik statesmanship of early modern Europe. According to Realism, world politics is always and necessarily a field of conflict among actors who want power. The theories of realism are contrasted by the cooperative ideals of liberalism.

Depending on what they see as the cause of the conflict between states, realists can be divided into three classes: Classical realists believe it follows from human nature; neorealists attribute it to the dynamics of the anarchic state system; neoclassical realists believe it results from both, in combination with domestic politics. Neorealists are also divided between defensive and offensive realism. Realists trace the history of their ideas back through classical antiquity, beginning with Thucydides.

Jonathan Haslam defines realism as "a spectrum of ideas." Its theories revolve around four main rules:

Realism is often associated with Realpolitik, as both deal with the pursuit, possession, and application of power. Realpolitik, however, is an older prescriptive guideline limited to policy-making, while realism is a wider theoretical and methodological paradigm to describe, explain, and predict events in international relations. As an academic pursuit, realism is not tied to ideology; it does not favor any particular moral philosophy, nor does it consider ideology to be a major factor in the behavior of nations. Priorities of realists have been described as Machiavellian, single-mindedly seeking the power of one's own nation over others.

[[Loris Zanatta]]

CATEGORIES: Italian historians, 1962 births, Living people, Italian academics

Loris Zanatta, born 1962, is Professor of Latin American History at the University of Bologna (Italy).

He is author of several books and articles, published in Europe and Latin America, and commentator on Latin America in various media.

Zanatta was featured in the 2018 documentary El pueblo soy yo.

[[Blagovest Sendov]]

Blagovest Hristov Sendov (Благовест Христов Сендов; 8 February 1932 – 19 January 2020) was a Bulgarian diplomat, mathematician and politician. He served as the chairperson of the National Assembly from 1995 to 1997. He was also the National Assembly's deputy chairperson from 1997 to 2002. He was the Bulgarian ambassador to Japan from 2004 to 2009. He was born in Asenovgrad.

On 19 January 2020, Sendov died at the age of 87.

[[Claudio Roditi]]

Cláudio Roditi (28 May 1946 – 17 January 2020) was a Brazilian jazz trumpeter. He was born in Rio de Janeiro. In 1976, he moved to New York City. Roditi was a member of Dizzy Gillespie's United Nations Orchestra. He also notably worked with Herbie Mann, Charlie Rouse and Paquito D'Rivera. He was nominated for two Grammy Awards in 1995 and 2010.

[[Jaroslav Kubera]]

CATEGORIES: 1947 births, 2020 deaths, Czech politicians, Mayors

Jaroslav Kubera (16 February 1947 – 20 January 2020) was a Czech politician. He was a member of the Civic Democratic Party (ODS). At the time of his death, he was the President of the Senate since November 2018. He was Senator from Teplice from 2000 until his death in 2020. He served as mayor of Teplice from 1994 to 2018.

Kubera was born in Louny. He had a small role as Edvard Beneš in historical drama movie Toman, directed by Ondřej Trojan.

Kubera died on 20 January 2020 in Ústí nad Labem. He was 72.

[[Lech Raczak]]

Lech Raczak (27 January 1946 – 17 January 2020) was a Polish theatre director. He was born in Krzyżanowo, Greater Poland Voivodeship, lived in  Poznań. He was one of the founders of the Theatre of the Eighth Day. From 1995 to 1998, Raczak was an artistic director of the Polish Theatre in Poznań. He also worked for Malta Festival as an artistic director between 1993 and 2012. He was a professor at University of Arts in Poznań from 2003.

Raczak died of a heart attack on 17 January 2020 at the age of 73.

[[DirectX Raytracing]]

CATEGORIES: Computer graphics

DirectX Raytracing (DXR) is a feature of Microsoft's DirectX that can do raytracing in real-time. It is a big development in computer graphics.The significance of this DirectX feature to the CG in general is currently doubtful, considering it's just a platform specific, hardware-accelerated implementation of a pre-existing rendering technique. It was first made to use Nvidia's Volta platform. Some of the first products for consumers that use DXR include the Nvidia GeForce 20 series of GPUs, which was announced in 2018. DXR came out as an extension to DirectX 12 instead of a new version of DirectX.

The Windows 10 October 2018 update includes the public release of DirectX Raytracing.

[[Bois de Sioux River]]

CATEGORIES: Rivers of Minnesota, Rivers of North Dakota, Rivers of South Dakota

The Bois de Sioux River drains Lake Traverse, the southernmost body of water in the Hudson Bay watershed of  North America. It is a tributary of the Red River of the North. It makes up part of the western border of the U.S. state of Minnesota, and the eastern borders of North Dakota and South Dakota. It is about 41 miles (66 km) in length. The Dakota name for this River is Caninkpa Wakpa ( can = wood; inkpa = point; wakpa = river) named because it is the point or beginning of the woods all the way to Hudson Bay.2 Where the Waters Gather and the Rivers Meet. By Paul C. Durand, Privately published, 1994 ISBN 0-9641469-0-8.

[[Bombshell (2019 movie)]]

It is based on the stories of many women at Fox News who set out to expose CEO Roger Ailes for sexual harassment. Actors John Lithgow, Kate McKinnon, Connie Britton, Malcolm McDowell, and Allison Janney appear in supporting roles.

Bombshell received generally favorable reviews.

[[La Bamba (movie)]]

CATEGORIES: 1987 drama movies, 1980s biographical movies, 1980s musical movies, American drama movies

La Bamba is a 1987 American biographical movie written and directed by Luis Valdez. It is about the life and career of Chicano rock 'n' roll star Ritchie Valens. The movie stars Lou Diamond Phillips as Valens, Esai Morales, Rosanna DeSoto, Elizabeth Peña, Danielle von Zerneck, and Joe Pantoliano. 

It was released on July 24, 1987 to positive reviews. In 2017, the movie was selected for preservation in the United States National Film Registry by the  Library of Congress as being "culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant".

[[Hudson County, New Jersey]]

CATEGORIES: New Jersey counties, 19th-century establishments in New Jersey, 1840 establishments in the United States

Hudson County, a county in the U.S. state of New Jersey. It is west of the lower Hudson River, which was named for Henry Hudson. The county seat is Jersey City.

As of the 2018 Census estimate, Hudson County was the fastest-growing county in New Jersey compared to 2010; the county's population was 676,061.

[[Egil Krogh]]

CATEGORIES: 1939 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from heart failure, Cardiovascular disease deaths in Washington, D.C., American lawyers, Politicians from Chicago, Politicians from Seattle, Washington, Criminals from Chicago, US Republican Party politicians

Egil "Bud" Krogh Jr. (August 3, 1939 – January 18, 2020) was an American lawyer and Republican politician. He was born in Chicago, but raised in Seattle. During the Richard Nixon presidency, he was the United States Under Secretary of Transportation from February 1973 through May 1973. 

Krogh was a key figure of the Watergate scandal as he was the person who approved the break-ins of the Watergate complex.

Krogh died on January 18, 2020 at a Washington, D.C. hospital from heart failure at the age of 80.

[[The Day the Music Died]]

CATEGORIES: 1959, 1950s in the United States

On February 3, 1959, American rock and roll musicians Buddy Holly, Ritchie Valens, and "The Big Bopper" J. P. Richardson were killed in a plane crash near Clear Lake, Iowa, together with pilot Roger Peterson.

The event later became known as "The Day the Music Died", after singer-songwriter Don McLean called it as such in his 1971 song "American Pie".

[[Ricky Ponting]]

CATEGORIES: 1974 births, Living people, Australian cricketers, Order of Australia, People from Launceston, Tasmania

Ricky Thomas Ponting AO (born 19 December 1974) is an Australian cricket coach, commentator and former cricketer. He is widely thought of as as one of the greatest batsmen of all time. 

Ponting captained his country between 2004 and 2011 in Tests and 2002 and 2011 in One Day Internationals (ODIs). With the Australian national team, he has won the World Cup three times, the ICC Champions Trophy twice and the Ashes once. He appeared in 168 Tests for Australia between 1995 and 2012. His first Test was against Sri Lanka and his last was against South Africa. He also played for Tasmania from 1992 to 2013.

Ponting has been assistant coach of the Australia national cricket team since February 2019.

Ponting was born in Launceston, Tasmania. He is married to Rianna Cantor. The couple have three children.

[[Steve Gillespie (wrestler)]]

CATEGORIES: 1963 births, 2020 deaths, Canadian professional wrestlers, Sportspeople from Calgary

Steve Gillespie (July 22, 1963 – January 18, 2020), better known under the ring name Dr. Hannibal, was a Canadian professional wrestler. He was born in Calgary, Alberta. He wrestled from 1987 until his retirement in 2013. He worked in promotions such as Stampede Wrestling, Canadian Rocky Mountain Wrestling, Frontier Martial-Arts Wrestling (FMW) and the World Wrestling Federation (WWF).

On January 18, 2020, Gillespie was found dead in his car in Calgary. He was 56.

[[Robert Parker (singer)]]

CATEGORIES: 1930 births, 2020 deaths, African-American singers, American R&B singers, Deaths from natural causes, Musicians from New Orleans, Louisiana

Robert Parker (October 14, 1930 – January 19, 2020) was an American R&B singer and musician. He was born in New Orleans, Louisiana. He is best known for his 1966 hit "Barefootin'". It sold over one million copies, and was awarded a gold disc by the RIAA. The song reached #2 on the U.S. Hot Rhythm & Blues Singles chart and #7 on the Billboard Hot 100. The single also charted in the United Kingdom.

On January 19, 2020, Parker died of natural causes in Roseland, Louisiana. He was 89.

[[Mario Bergamaschi]]

CATEGORIES: 1929 births, 2020 deaths, A.C. Milan players, Italian footballers, Sportspeople from Lombardy

Mario Bergamaschi (7 January 1929 – 18 January 2020) was an Italian footballer. He played as a midfielder.

Bergamaschi was born in Crema, Lombardy. He played for 14 seasons in Serie A for Como (1950–1953), Milan (1953–1958) and Sampdoria (1958–1964). He also played for the Italy national team, playing his first game against Argentina in 1954.

Bergamaschi died on 18 January 2020 in Crema. He was 91.

[[Roseland, Louisiana]]

CATEGORIES: Towns in Louisiana

Roseland is a town in Tangipahoa Parish, Louisiana, United States. The population was 1,162 at the 2000 census.

[[Joseph Hannesschläger]]

CATEGORIES: 1962 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from neuroendocrine cancer, Cancer deaths in Germany, German musicians, German movie actors, German television actors, German stage actors, German voice actors, People from Munich

Joseph Hannesschläger (2 June 1962 – 20 January 2020) was a German actor and musician. He was born in Munich. He played the main role of Chief of Police Korbinian Hofer in Die Rosenheim-Cops from 2002 to 2019.

In October 2019, Hannesschläger was diagnosed with neuroendocrine cancer. He died from the disease in Munich on 20 January 2020 at the age of 57. 

[[Ismat Ara Sadique]]

CATEGORIES: 1942 births, 2020 deaths, Bangladeshi politicians, Bangladeshi Muslims

Ismat Ara Sadique (12 December 1942 – 21 January 2020) was a Bangladeshi politician. She was the Minister of Ministry of Public Administration from 2014 to 2018. She was a member of Jatiya Sangsad from 2014 until 2020. She was a member of the Awami League.

Sadique died on 21 January 2020 in Dhaka at the age of 77.

[[Percy Heath]]

CATEGORIES: 1923 births, 2005 deaths, Deaths from bone cancer, Cancer deaths in New York, American jazz musicians, Musicians from North Carolina

Percy Heath (April 30, 1923 – April 28, 2005) was an American jazz bassist. He was the brother of saxophonist Jimmy Heath and drummer Albert Heath, with whom he formed the Heath Brothers in 1975. 

Heath played with the Modern Jazz Quartet throughout their long history and also worked with Miles Davis, Dizzy Gillespie, Charlie Parker, Wes Montgomery, and Thelonious Monk.

[[Kenny Burrell]]

CATEGORIES: 1931 births, Living people, American jazz musicians, American soul musicians, American blues musicians, American guitarists, American educators, Musicians from Detroit, Michigan

Kenneth Earl Burrell (born July 31, 1931) is an American jazz guitarist. He is known for his work on the Blue Note label. His works with Jimmy Smith produced the 1965 Billboard Top Twenty hit album Organ Grinder Swing. 

Jimi Hendrix has said Burrell as an inspiration.

Burrell is a professor and Director of Jazz Studies at the UCLA Herb Alpert School of Music.

[[Curtis Fuller]]

CATEGORIES: 1934 births, 2021 deaths, American composers, American educators, American soul musicians, American jazz musicians, American trombonists, Musicians from Detroit, Michigan

Curtis DuBois Fuller (December 15, 1934 – May 8, 2021) was an American jazz trombonist. He was known as a member of Art Blakey's Jazz Messengers and worked with many classic jazz recordings.

Fuller was a faculty member of the New York State Summer School of the Arts (NYSSSA) School of Jazz Studies (SJS).

Fuller died on May 8, 2021 in New York City at the age of 86.

[[Benny Golson]]

CATEGORIES: 1929 births, Living people, American composers, American jazz musicians, American saxophonists, Musicians from Philadelphia, Pennsylvania

Benny Golson (born January 25, 1929) is an American bebop/hard bop jazz tenor saxophonist, composer, and arranger. He was a member of Lionel Hampton and Dizzy Gillespie led bands. Golson is known for co-founding and co-leading The Jazztet with trumpeter Art Farmer in 1959.  His best known song is "I Remember Clifford".

[[Aloïse Moudileno Massengo]]

CATEGORIES: 1933 births, 2020 deaths, African politicians, Lawyers, Republic of the Congo, Vice presidents

Aloïse Moudileno Massengo (11 March 1933 – 6 January 2020) was a Congolese politician and lawyer. He served as Vice President of the Republic of the Congo from 1971 to 1972. He has been called the first Congolese lawyer. He was born in Vindza District.

Moudileno Massengo died on 6 January 2020 in the French city of Nancy. He was 86.

[[David Olney]]

CATEGORIES: 1948 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from myocardial infarction, Cardiovascular disease deaths in Florida, American singer-songwriters, American folk singers, American folk musicians, American guitarists, People from Providence, Rhode Island, Singers from Rhode Island, Musicians from Rhode Island, Writers from Rhode Island, Singers from Nashville, Tennessee, Musicians from Nashville, Tennessee, Writers from Nashville, Tennessee

David Charles Olney (March 23, 1948 – January 18, 2020) was an American folk singer-songwriter. He was born in Providence, Rhode Island. Olney performed as a solo singer-songwriter, and released more than 20 albums over forty years. He worked with artists such as John Hadley and Sergio Webb. 

His songs were covered by and co-written with Emmylou Harris, Steve Earle, Linda Ronstadt, Steve Young, Del McCoury, and Laurie Lewis, among others.

Olney died of a heart attack during a performance onstage at the 30A Songwriter Festival in Santa Rosa Beach, Florida, on January 18, 2020, at age 71. 

[[Del McCoury]]

CATEGORIES: 1939 births, Living people, American country guitarists, American bluegrass musicians, American bandleaders, Singers from Pennsylvania, Musicians from Pennsylvania

Delano Floyd "Del" McCoury (born February 1, 1939) is an American bluegrass musician and singer. He was leader of the Del McCoury Band. He plays guitar and sings lead vocals along with his two sons, Ronnie McCoury and Rob McCoury.

In June 2010, he received a National Heritage Fellowship lifetime achievement award from the National Endowment for the Arts and in 2011 he was elected into the International Bluegrass Music Hall of Fame.

[[Ivan Ustinov]]

CATEGORIES: 1920 births, 2020 deaths, Soviet military people, Centenarians

Ivan Lavrentevich Ustinov (Иван Лаврентьевич Устинов; 1 January 1920 – 15 January 2020) was a Soviet intelligence officer. He had many posts in Soviet military counterintelligence, reaching the rank of general-lieutenant. He was Third Directorate of the KGB and Office of Special Divisions of the KGB for the Group of Soviet Forces in Germany.

Ustinov died in Moscow on 15 January 2020 at the age of 100.

[[Hwang Sun-hui]]

CATEGORIES: 1919 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from pneumonia, North Korean politicians, Military personnel of World War II, Centenarians

Hwang Sun-hui (황순희, 3 May 1919 – 17 January 2020) was a North Korean politician and military personnel. She worked in many top-ranking positions in the Workers' Party of Korea (WPK). She worked in the Supreme People's Assembly and the Central Committee of the WPK. She was a member of the Korean Revolution Museum since 1965, and was its director since 1990. She was born in North Hamgyong Province.

Hwang died on 17 January 2020 in Pyongyang of pneumonia at the age of 100.

[[Wolfgang J. Fuchs]]

CATEGORIES: 1945 births, 2020 deaths, German historians, Translators, Editors

Wolfgang J. Fuchs (16 September 1945 – 20 January 2020) was a German historian and comic book translator. He was born in Unsleben, Germany. He was known as the main editor of Die tollsten Geschichten von Donald Duck – Sonderheft, a German Disney comic. He was also known for his comic Disneys Heimliche Helden (2005–2009).

Fuchs died on 20 January 2020 in Munich at the age of 74.

[[Marc Morgan]]

CATEGORIES: 1962 births, 2020 deaths, Belgian singers, People from Huy, Singer-songwriters

Marc Wathieu (30 April 1962 – 10 January 2020), better known as Marc Morgan, was a Belgian singer and songwriter. He was born in Huy. His single "Notre Mystère, nos reunions" reached the French top 50 charts in 1993. He also worked as a professor. He worked at the École de recherche graphique in Brussels, the École supérieure des arts Le 75 in Woluwe-Saint-Lambert and the Haute école Albert Jacquard in Namur.

Morgan died on 10 January 2020, at the age of 57.

[[Robert Molimard]]

CATEGORIES: 1927 births, 2020 deaths, French educators, French physicians, People from Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes

Robert Molimard (16 December 1927 – 9 January 2020) was a French doctor. He served as a professor at Paris-Sud University. He was a pioneer in tobacco research in France. He worked on four publications. His last publication was L’Homme, avatar de Dieu in 2016.

Molimard was born in Cournon-d'Auvergne. He died on 9 January 2020, at the age of 92.

[[Red brick university]]

CATEGORIES: Universities in the United Kingdom

A red brick university (or redbrick university) was one of the nine civic universities founded in the major industrial cities of England. They are founded in the 19th century. These universities were different from other universities as they accepted students regardless of religion or background. They concentrated on imparting to their students "real-world" skills such as engineering and medicine. 

[[Endocarp]]

CATEGORIES: Botany, Plant anatomy

Endocarp is the inside of the fruit, particularly of the Valencia navel orange hesperidium. You may also refer to the endocarp as the carpel or pulp of the orange. Exocarp or  would be the outside skin or rind of the fruit.

[[Eugène Berger]]

CATEGORIES: 1960 births, 2020 deaths, Educators, Luxembourgian politicians, Luxembourgian sportspeople, Mountain climbers

Eugène Berger (4 December 1960 – 21 January 2020) was a Luxembourg politician, teacher and alpinist. He was a member of the Democratic Party. At the time of his death in 2020, he was a member of the Chamber of Deputies since 2007. He was first elected to the Chamber of Deputies in 1994, serving until 2004. He was State Secretary of the Environment from 1999 to 2004.

In 1992, Berger became the first Luxembourger to climb Mount Everest. For this feat, he won the title of Luxembourgian Sportsman of the Year.

Berger was born in Bettembourg. He had two children. He died on 21 January 2020, at the age of 59.

[[Independent city (United States)]]

CATEGORIES: Local government in the United States

In the United States, an independent city is a city that does not belong to any particular county. The United States has 41 independent cities: 38 in Virginia (whose state constitution designates all municipalities incorporated as "cities" as such), plus Baltimore, Maryland; St. Louis, Missouri; and Carson City, Nevada.

[[Donetsk People's Republic]]

CATEGORIES: Unrecognized countries, Puppet states

Donetsk People’s Republic is an unrecognized state in the Donbass region of Ukraine. When the War in Donbass started in 2014, a few hundred separatists proclaimed it in part of Donetsk Oblast. Donetsk Oblast is all to the east of Ukraine, at the border with Russia. Approximately at the same time, other people started Luhansk People's Republic in Luhansk Oblast.  In both parts, there are many ethnic Russians. Russia aided the start of these non-recognised states.

[[Kate Malone]]

Kate Olivia Malone GBR (born 29 January 1959) in London, is a British potter and ceramic artist. With Keith Brymer Jones, she judges BBC2’s The Great Pottery Throw Down. She is known for her large sculptures and using bright colors.

[[Ian Tuxworth]]

CATEGORIES: 1942 births, 2020 deaths, Chief Ministers of the Northern Territory, Politicians from New South Wales

Ian Lindsay Tuxworth  (18 June 1942 – 21 January 2020) was an Australian politician. He was a member of the Country Liberal Party and later the Northern Territory Nationals. He served as the second Chief Minister of the Northern Territory from 1984 until he resigned in 1986. He was also elected to the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly in 1974.

Tuxworth was born in Wollongong, New South Wales. In 1951, he moved to Tennant Creek, Northern Territory. Tuxworth died on 21 January 2020 in Perth, Western Australia. He was 77.

[[Public]]

In communication science and public relations, "public" mostly means people. The meaning of this is different than other ideas, such as gatherings in social life to talk about people (public sphere). The meaning of this is also talked about in the learning of government (political science), the learning of how humans think (psychology), and the learning of giving things to people (marketing). This word's meaning is very hard to make, as people think that public has different meanings.

[[Barbara Barrett]]

CATEGORIES: 1950 births, Living people, United States Secretaries of the Air Force, Ambassadors of the United States, American lawyers, Businesspeople from Pennsylvania, Politicians from Pennsylvania, Politicians from Arizona, US Republican Party politicians

Barbara McConnell Barrett (born December 26, 1950) is an American politician, businesswoman, and lawyer. She was the 25th United States Secretary of the Air Force from October 18, 2019 to January 20, 2021.

From May 23, 2008 through January 16, 2009, she was the United States Ambassador to Finland for the George W. Bush administration.

Barrett was former chair of the Aerospace Corporation and a member on the boards of California Institute of Technology, Jet Propulsion Laboratory, RAND Corporation, Smithsonian Institution, Horatio Alger Association of Distinguished Americans, and Lasker Foundation.

On May 21, 2019, President Donald Trump announced he would nominate Barrett as Secretary of the Air Force. Her nomination was confirmed with an 85-7 U.S. Senate vote on October 18, 2019. She was sworn in October 18, 2019.

[[Sam Aston]]

CATEGORIES: 1993 births, Living people, English television actors, Actors from Lancashire

Samuel David Aston (born 7 June 1993) is an English actor, known for playing the role of Chesney Brown on the ITV soap opera Coronation Street. Aston made his television debut at the age of five, as an extra in Eddie Mountain.

Aston was awarded Best Newcomer at the National Television Awards in 2004. He also won Best Dramatic Performance for a Young Actor or Actress at the British Soap Awards.

[[Impeachment process against Richard Nixon]]

CATEGORIES: 1974 in the United States, Watergate scandal

The impeachment process against Richard Nixon began in the United States House of Representatives on October 30, 1973, following the "Saturday Night Massacre" episode of the Watergate scandal. 

The House Committee on the Judiciary set up an impeachment inquiry staff and began investigations into possible impeachable offenses by Richard Nixon, the 37th president of the United States. 

The process began on February 6, 1974, when the House granted the Judiciary Committee authority to investigate whether sufficient grounds existed to impeach President Nixon of high crimes and misdemeanors under Article II, Section 4, of the United States Constitution. 

This investigation happened one year after the United States Senate created the Select Committee on Presidential Campaign Activities to investigate the 1972 break-in at the Democratic National Committee headquarters at the Watergate hotel in Washington, D.C..

On August 9, 1974, before the full House could vote on the articles of impeachment, Nixon resigned thus ending the impeachment process.

[[Chamber of Deputies (Luxembourg)]]

CATEGORIES: Luxembourg

The Chamber of Deputies (D'Chamber, Chambre des Députés, Abgeordnetenkammer), abbreviated to the Chamber, is the unicameral national legislature of Luxembourg. The Chamber is made up of 60 seats. Deputies are elected to have five-year terms by proportional representation in four multi-seat constituencies. Voters may vote for as many candidates as the constituency elects deputies.

[[Joe Shishido]]

CATEGORIES: 1933 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from myocardial infarction, Japanese movie actors

Joe Shishido was a Japanese actor. He appeared in some 300 movies, but was best known in the West for his performance in the cult movie Branded to Kill (1967). 

In Japan, he was also known by the nickname Joe the Ace for his popular role in the Western Fast-Draw Guy (1961). He was born in Kita, Osaka, Japan.

Shishido died on January 20, 2020 of a suspected heart attack in Tokyo at the age of 86.

[[De'Runnya Wilson]]

CATEGORIES: 1994 births, 2020 deaths, African American players of American football, American football wide receivers, Murdered African-American people, Sportspeople from Birmingham, Alabama

De'Runnya S. Wilson (September 14, 1994 – January 21, 2020) was an American football player. He played as a wide receiver. At the time of his death in 2020, he played for Albany Empire of the Arena Football League (AFL). He played college football at Mississippi State. He was born in Birmingham, Alabama.

Wilson died on January 21, 2020 in Birmingham, Alabama. He was 25. Police treated his death as a murder.

[[Theodor Wagner]]

CATEGORIES: 1927 births, 2020 deaths, Austrian footballers, Austrian football managers, 1948 Summer Olympics, 1954 FIFA World Cup players, Sportspeople from Vienna

Theodor "Turl" Wagner (6 August 1927 – 21 January 2020) was an Austrian footballer. He played as a striker.

Wagner was born in Vienna. He played club football between 1946 and 1964. He played for Wacker Wien, Linz and Wacker Innsbruck.

Wagner played for Austria between 1946 and 1957. He played 46 times for his country, and scored 22 goals. He was part of the 1954 FIFA World Cup squad that finished third. He famously scored a hat-trick in Austria's 7–5 quarterfinal win over Switzerland at the 1954 FIFA World Cup.

Wagner died on 21 January 2020 in Vienna. He was 92.

[[Antelope Valley]]

CATEGORIES: Valleys of California, Kern County, California, Geography of Los Angeles County, California

Antelope Valley is in northern Los Angeles County, California, and the southeast part of Kern County, California. It is a part of the western tip of the Mojave Desert. It is between the Tehachapi, Sierra Pelona, and the San Gabriel Mountains.  

The valley was named for the pronghorns that roamed there. They were killed in the 1880s, mostly by hunting, or moved to other areas. The main cities in the Antelope Valley are Palmdale and Lancaster.

[[Joyce Bryant]]

CATEGORIES: 1927 births, Living people, American jazz singers, American pop singers, American gospel singers, American dancers, American movie actors, American television actors, American civil rights activists, American stage actors, American autobiographers, Musicians from California, Singers from California, Writers from California, Actors from Oakland, California, Actors from Huntsville, Alabama, Musicians from Huntsville, Alabama, Singers from Huntsville, Alabama, Writers from Huntsville, Alabama

Joyce Bryant (born October 14, 1927) is an African-American singer and actress. She was popular in the late 1940s and early 1950s as a theater and nightclub performer.

She became an early African-American sex symbol. She had nicknames such as "The Bronze Blond Bombshell", "the black Marilyn Monroe", "The Belter", and "The Voice You'll Always Remember".

Point Clear is an unincorporated community and census-designated place (CDP) in Baldwin County, Alabama, United States. As of the 2010 census, the population was 2,125. It is part of the Daphne–Fairhope–Foley Micropolitan Statistical Area.

[[The Wayfaring Stranger (song)]]

CATEGORIES: Songs

"The Wayfaring Stranger" (also known as "Poor Wayfaring Stranger" or "I Am a Poor Wayfaring Stranger"), Roud 3339, is a famous American folk and gospel song probably coming from the early 1800s about a soul on the journey through life. There are many versions of the song. During a period during and several years after the American Civil War, the lyrics were known as the Libby Prison Hymn (named after a Confederate prison).

[[Emmylou Harris]]

CATEGORIES: Grammy Award winners, 1947 births, Living people, American singer-songwriters, American country guitarists, American country singers, American rock guitarists, American rock singers, American folk singers, American folk musicians, Singers from Birmingham, Alabama, Musicians from Birmingham, Alabama, Writers from Birmingham, Alabama

Emmylou Harris (born April 2, 1947) is an American singer-songwriter, and musician. She was born in Birmingham, Alabama. She has won 14 Grammys. Harris was added into the Country Music Hall of Fame.

[[Zazie Beetz]]

[[CNET]]

CATEGORIES: Webby Award winners, American websites, 1994 establishments in California

CNET (written as c|net) is formerly known as  Computer Network. Founded in 1994 by Halsey Minor and Shelby Bonnie, it was the flagship brand of CNET Networks and became a brand of CBS Interactive through that unit's acquisition of CNET Networks in 2008, which was the previous owner prior to October 30, 2020. Red Ventures owned CNET since 2020. CNET originally produced content for radio and television in addition to its website and now uses new media distribution methods through its Internet television network, CNET Video, and its podcast and blog networks.

It is an American media website that publishes reviews, news, articles, blogs, podcasts and videos on global technology and consumer electronics.  CNET has the highest readership among web news sites. It has over 200 million readers per month. It is among the 200 most visited websites globally in 2015.

[[Dizi (instrument)]]

A Dizi is a flute type instrument like a bass flute and made from bamboo.

[[Paul Everingham]]

CATEGORIES: 1943 births, Living people, Chief Ministers of the Northern Territory, Order of Australia, Politicians from Brisbane

Paul Anthony Edward Everingham AUS (born 4 February 1943) is an Australian politician. He was a member of the Country Liberal Party. He was the head of government of the Northern Territory from 1977 to 1984. He served as the second and last Majority Leader (1977–1978) and the first Chief Minister of the Northern Territory from 1978 to 1984. He also served as a member of the national parliament for the Northern Territory from 1984 to 1987.

Everingham was born in Brisbane, Queensland.

[[Carina Driscoll]]

CATEGORIES: Living people, State legislators of the United States, Politicians from Vermont, People from Burlington, Vermont, Bernie Sanders

Carina Driscoll is an American politician. She was a State Representative in the Vermont House of Representatives for the Chittenden District from 2001 to 2003. She is a co-founder of Vermont Woodworking school with her husband Blake Ewoldson. 

She unsuccessfully ran for Mayor of Burlington, Vermont in 2018. She is the stepdaughter of U.S. Senator Bernie Sanders and daughter of Jane O'Meara Sanders.

[[Steve Rayner]]

CATEGORIES: 1953 births, 2020 deaths, British sociologists, British critics, Deaths from cancer

Steve Rayner (22 May 1953 – 17 January 2020) was a British sociologist. He was the James Martin Professor of Science and Civilization at Oxford University and Director of the Institute for Science, Innovation and Society. He was a member of the Oxford Martin School. He was known for his work for stopping climate change and for criticizing non-eco friendly engineers. 

In 2008, he was listed by Wired Magazine as one of the 15 people the next President should listen to and was recognized for his works to the joint award of the 2007 Nobel Peace Prize to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC).

Rayner died of cancer on 17 January 2020, aged 66.

[[Katerina Sakellaropoulou]]

CATEGORIES: 1956 births, Greek judges, Living people, Presidents of Greece, Current national leaders

Katerina Sakellaropoulou (Greek: Κατερίνα Σακελλαροπούλου, born 30 May 1956) is a Greek politician. She is the 13th President of Greece. She took office on 13 March 2020. She was elected to replace Prokopis Pavlopoulos by parliament on 22 January 2020. Sakellaropoulou is Greece's first female president.

[[Speaker of the Hellenic Parliament]]

CATEGORIES: Speakers of the Hellenic Parliament

The Speaker, properly the President of the Hellenic Parliament (Πρόεδρος της Βουλής των Ελλήνων) is the presiding officer of the Parliament of Greece. 

The official order of precedence ranks the Speaker of the Hellenic Parliament in the 3rd position, after the President of the Republic and the Prime Minister.

The current Speaker is Konstantinos Tasoulas of New Democracy.

[[Konstantinos Tasoulas]]

CATEGORIES: 1959 births, Living people, Speakers of the Hellenic Parliament, Mayors

Konstantinos Tasoulas (Κωνσταντίνος Τασούλας; born 17 July 1959) is a Greek politician. He is the Speaker of the Hellenic Parliament since 18 July 2019. 

He was Minister of Culture and Sports, Deputy Minister of National Defence and Mayor of Kifissia.

[[Zoe Konstantopoulou]]

CATEGORIES: 1976 births, People from Athens, Living people, Greek lawyers, Speakers of the Hellenic Parliament

Zoe Konstantopoulou (Ζωή Κωνσταντοπούλου; born 8 December 1976) is a Greek lawyer and politician. She was President of the Hellenic Parliament in 2015. She was elected to the post on 6 February 2015 with the record number of 235 out of 300 votes. She is President of the political party Course of Freedom.

[[Anna Benaki-Psarouda]]

CATEGORIES: 1934 births, Living people, People from Athens, Greek lawyers, Greek educators, Speakers of the Hellenic Parliament, Women lawyers

Anna Benaki-Psarouda (born 12 December 1934) is a Greek lawyer, New Democracy politician and academician. She was born in Athens. She was Minister of Justice. From 2004 to 2007 she was Speaker of the Hellenic Parliament.

In 2010 she was elected Member of the Academy of Athens.

[[Apostolos Kaklamanis]]

CATEGORIES: 1936 births, Living people, Speakers of the Hellenic Parliament

Apostolos Kaklamanis (Απόστολος Κακλαμάνης) (born September 7, 1936) is a Greek politician. He is a member of the Greek Parliament for the Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK) for the Athens B constituency. He was born in Lefkada, Greece.

He was Minister of Employment (2 terms), Minister for National Education and Religious Affairs (2 terms), Minister for Justice, Minister for Research and Technology and Minister for Health and Social Solidarity.

He was Speaker of the Hellenic Parliament from 22 October 1993 to 18 July 2004.

[[Hellenic Parliament]]

CATEGORIES: Politics of Greece

The Hellenic Parliament (Ελληνικό Κοινοβούλιο, transliterated Elliniko Kinovoulio), in Greek known as Voulí ton Ellínon (Βουλή των Ελλήνων, literally Parliament of the Hellenes) is the parliament of Greece. It is  located in the Old Royal Palace in Athens. The Parliament represents the citizens through an elected body of Members of Parliament (MPs).

It is a unicameral legislature of 300 members, elected for a four-year term. The leading person of the parliament is known as the Speaker of the Hellenic Parliament.

[[Leader of the Opposition (Greece)]]

CATEGORIES: Greek politicians

The Leader of the Opposition (Αρχηγός της Αξιωματικής Αντιπολίτευσης) is the politician who leads the official Opposition in Greece.

The Leader of the Opposition is normally the leader of the largest party not within the government, which is usually the second largest political party in the Hellenic Parliament.

[[May Wynn]]

CATEGORIES: 1928 births, Living people, Actors from New York City, American dancers, American movie actors, American television actors, Singers from New York City

Donna Lee Custer (née Hickey; born January 8, 1928), better known as May Wynn, is a retired American dancer, singer and actress. Her acting career lasted from around 1952 to 1960. She notably appeared in The Caine Mutiny (1954), The Violent Men (1955), The Man Is Armed (1956) and Perry Mason (1959).

Wynn was born in New York City. In 1956, Wynn married actor Jack Kelly in Quartzsite, Arizona. The couple divorced in 1964. She was married to her second husband Jack W. Custer from 1968 to 1979.

[[Quartzsite, Arizona]]

Quartzsite is a town in La Paz County, Arizona, United States. As of the 2010 census, the town had a population of 3,677.

[[Nazanin Afshin-Jam]]

Nazanin Afshin-Jam (نازنین افشین جم, Nāzanin Afŝin Jam, born April 11, 1979) is an Iranian-Canadian singer, model, public speaker and human rights activist. She is a former Miss World Canada. She is also president and co-founder of Stop Child Executions as well as the founder of "The Nazanin Foundation".

She is married to Peter MacKay, former Minister of Justice and Attorney General of Canada.

[[George Herbert Walker III]]

CATEGORIES: 1931 births, 2020 deaths, Deaths from stroke, Bush family, Ambassadors of the United States, American philanthropists, Businesspeople from St. Louis, Missouri, Politicians from St. Louis, Missouri, US Republican Party politicians

George Herbert "Bert" Walker III (March 16, 1931 – January 20, 2020) was an American businessman, diplomat and philanthropist. He was the U.S. Ambassador to Hungary from 2003 to 2006. He was born in St. Louis, Missouri. He was the cousin of Presidents George H. W. and George W. Bush.

Walker III died on January 20, 2020 under hospice care in Creve Coeur, Missouri of stroke-related problems at the age of 88.

[[Dee Hartford]]

CATEGORIES: 1928 births, Living people, Actors from Salt Lake City, Utah, American models, American movie actors, American television actors

Dee Hartford (born Donna Higgins; April 21, 1928) is a retired American actress and model. She worked as a model for Vogue in the late 1940s. She is known for her acting roles in A Girl in Every Port, Red Line 7000, Perry Mason, The Twilight Zone, Gunsmoke, Burke's Law, The Outer Limits, The Alfred Hitchcock Hour, Batman, Time Tunnel, Land of the Giants and Lost in Space.

Hartford was born in Salt Lake City, Utah. Her sister, actress Eden Hartford, was married to Groucho Marx. Hartford was married to movie director Howard Marks from 1953 to 1959.

[[Nizhnekamsky District]]

CATEGORIES: Tatarstan

Nizhnekamsky District is a district of Tatarstan. It lies near the Kama (Chulman) River. Tatar, Russian, Chuvash and other people live in Nizhnekamsky District.

There is a famous Holy Spring in Krasny Klyuch near the town of Nizhnekamsk.

Nizhnekamsk town newspapers - Hezmattash Avazi ("Voice of the counterpart), etc. 

[[George Gregan]]

CATEGORIES: 1973 births, Living people, Australian rugby union players, Order of Australia, People from Canberra

George Musarurwa Gregan AM (born 19 April 1973) is a retired Australian rugby union player. He played as a scrum-half. He is Australia's highest ever internationally capped player. He made 139 appearances for his country. He won the 1999 Rugby World Cup. As captain of Australia, he won the Bledisloe Cup in 2002 and lost the final of the 2003 Rugby World Cup against England. He also played for the Brumbies between 1996 and 2007.

Gregan was born in Lusaka, Zambia. He is the son of a Zimbabwean mother and an Australian father. He grew up in Canberra, Australian Capital Territory. Gregan is married to Erica and has three children.

[[Mike Medavoy]]

CATEGORIES: 1941 births, Living people, American chief executives, American Jews, American movie producers, American television producers, People from Shanghai, Naturalized citizens of the United States

Morris Mike Medavoy (born January 21, 1941) is an American movie producer and executive. He is the current chairman and CEO of Phoenix Pictures. He is also the co-founder of Orion Pictures (1978), former chairman of TriStar Pictures and former head of production for United Artists (1974–1978). He has served as a producer for movies such as The Thin Red Line (1998), The 6th Day (2000), Vertical Limit (2000), Basic (2003), Holes (2003), Stealth (2005), All the King's Men (2006), Miss Potter (2006), Pathfinder (2007), Resurrecting the Champ (2007), Zodiac (2007), License to Wed (2007), Shutter Island (2010), Shanghai (2010), Black Swan (2010), What to Expect When You're Expecting (2012) and  The 33 (2015).

Medavoy was born in the Chinese city of Shanghai. His parents were Russian Jews. He lived in Chile from 1947 to 1957. He became an American citizen in 1963. He has been married four times. He has two children, including Brian Medavoy.

[[Alison King]]

CATEGORIES: 1973 births, Living people, English television actors, English movie actors, People from Leicester

Alison Rosamund King (born 3 March 1973) is an English actress and model. She is known for her television roles as Lynda Block in the Sky One drama series Dream Team and Carla Connor in the long-running ITV soap opera Coronation Street. She won Best Actress at the 2012 British Soap Awards.

King is considered by the press as a British sex symbol.

[[Quipu]]

CATEGORIES: Inca civilization, Media

Quipu are ancient Inca tools for recording information. They are colored threads knotted in different ways.

[[Elephantine]]

CATEGORIES: Ancient Egypt, Archaeological sites in Egypt, Cities in Egypt, Geography of Egypt, History of Egypt, Islands of Africa, World Heritage Sites in Egypt

Elephantine is an island in the River Nile, which forms part of the city of Aswan, Egypt. It is about 1200 by 400 in size. People have lived there since Ancient Egyptian times. Today, there are a number of ruins on the island. It also features a botanical garden with a large collection of palm trees.

[[Wells Fargo Place]]

CATEGORIES: Buildings and structures in Minnesota, Saint Paul, Minnesota

Wells Fargo Place (30 East 7th Street) is an office tower in Saint Paul, Minnesota, United States. It stands at 471 tall, and is currently the tallest building in Saint Paul. It was designed by Winsor/Faricy Architects, Inc. and WZMH Architects, and is 37 stories tall. 

The building opened in September 1987. It was formerly known as The Minnesota World Trade Center. Anthrosphere, a large sculpture by Paul Granlund, is in the lobby.

LeClair was a member of the Montreal Canadiens' Stanley Cup winning team in 1993.

[[Harold Kelley]]

CATEGORIES: 1921 births, 2003 deaths, American psychologists, People from Boise, Idaho, Scientists from Idaho, Scientists from Los Angeles, California

Harold Kelley (February 16, 1921 – January 29, 2003) was an American social psychologist. He was born in Boise, Idaho. He was professor of psychology at the University of California, Los Angeles. His major works were the development of interdependence theory (with John Thibaut). A Review of General Psychology survey, published in 2002, ranked Kelley as the 43rd most cited psychologist of the 20th century.

[[David Schindler]]

CATEGORIES: 1940 births, 2021 deaths, Canadian educators, Canadian scientists, American educators, Scientists from North Dakota, People from Fargo, North Dakota, People from Edmonton

David William Schindler, CAN, (August 3, 1940 – March 4, 2021) was an American/Canadian limnologist. He holds the Killam Memorial Chair and is Professor of Ecology in the Department of Biological Sciences at the University of Alberta in Edmonton, Alberta.  He was known for "innovative large-scale experiments" on whole lakes at the Experimental Lakes Area (ELA). He was also known for his research on acid rain.

[[Neal D. Barnard]]

Neal D. Barnard (born July 10, 1953) is an American author and clinical researcher. He was the founding president of the Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine (PCRM). He was known for his medical research about acne.

[[Samuel Ward King]]

Samuel Ward King (May 23, 1786 – January 20, 1851) was an American politician and physician. He was the 15th Governor of Rhode Island from 1839 to 1843.

[[Rensis Likert]]

CATEGORIES: 1903 births, 1981 deaths, American psychologists, Scientists from Wyoming, People from Cheyenne, Wyoming

Rensis Likert (ˈ LIK; August 5, 1903 – September 3, 1981) was an American social psychologist. He is known for creating the 5-point Likert scale, a scale that allows people to respond to questions of interest, in order to measure people's attitudes.

He wrote many books including; New Ways of Managing Conflict (1976) and Human Organization: Its Management and Value (1967). 

[[Aiea, Hawaii]]

CATEGORIES: Census-designated places in Hawaii

Aiea (Hawaiian: okinaAiea) is a census-designated place (CDP) in Honolulu County, Hawaii, United States. As of the 2010 census, the CDP had a population of 9,338.

[[Aloha Stadium]]

CATEGORIES: 1975 establishments in the United States, Buildings and structures in Hawaii, Sports buildings in the United States

Aloha Stadium is a stadium in Honolulu, Hawaii, United States. It is the largest stadium in the state of Hawaii. It is located in the western Honolulu suburb of Halawa. The stadium is home to the University of Hawaiokinai Rainbow Warriors football team (Mountain West Conference, NCAA Division I FBS).

The stadium opened in 1975. It has a seating capacity of 50,000.

[[Halawa, Hawaii]]

CATEGORIES: Census-designated places in Hawaii

Halawa is a census-designated place (CDP) in Honolulu County, Hawaii, United States. As of the 2010 census, the CDP had a population of 14,014. Aloha Stadium is located in Halawa.

Halawa is also the site of Aloha Stadium which is home to the University of Hawaii Warriors football team and many other sporting events. On the ocean side of Halawa is Pearl Harbor. Halawa Valley becomes wider near Pearl Harbor and this is where most of the residential neighborhoods are located.

Halawa Valley has many important cultural sites dating to ancient times. This led to many protests during the building of the H-3 Freeway which opened in 1997 running right through the valley.

[[B. Frank Heintzleman]]

CATEGORIES: 1888 births, 1963 deaths, Governors of Alaska, Scientists from Alaska, Politicians from Pennsylvania, Scientists from Pennsylvania, US Republican Party politicians

Benjamin Franklin Heintzleman (December 3, 1888 – June 24, 1965) was an American forester and politician. He was Governor of Alaska Territory, a position he held from 1953 till 1957.  Heintzleman's resignation became effective on January 4, 1957, when Territorial Secretary became Acting Governor.

[[Fayetteville, Pennsylvania]]

Fayetteville is an unincorporated community and census-designated place (CDP) in Franklin County, Pennsylvania, United States. The population was 3,128 at the 2010 census, up from 2,774 at the 2000 census.

[[Ruth A. M. Schmidt]]

Ruth Anna Marie Schmidt (April 22, 1916 – March 29, 2014) was an American geologist and paleontologist. She created a United States Geological Survey (USGS) field office in Alaska and the first Department of Geology at the Anchorage Community College.

[[Chris Birch (politician)]]

[[Taylor Wilson]]

CATEGORIES: Living people, 1994 births, American physicists, American engineers, People from Reno, Nevada, Scientists from Arkansas, Scientists from Nevada

Taylor Ramon Wilson (born May 7, 1994) is an American nuclear physics enthusiast and science activist. In 2008, at the age of 14, he produced nuclear fusion using a fusor and at the time was the youngest person ever to do so.

[[Raye Montague]]

CATEGORIES: 1935 births, 2018 deaths, Deaths from heart failure, American military people, American engineers, Scientists from Arkansas, People from Little Rock, Arkansas

Raye Jean Montague (née Jordan; January 21, 1935 – October 10, 2018) was an American naval engineer. She was known for creating the first computer-generated rough draft of a U.S. naval ship. She was the first female program manager of ships in the United States Navy.

[[Ruth Haas]]

CATEGORIES: Scientists from Hawaii, American mathematicians, Living people, American educators, Year of birth missing (living people)

Ruth Haas is an American mathematician and professor at the University of Hawaii at Manoa. She was the Achilles Professor of Mathematics at Smith College. She won the M. Gweneth Humphreys Award from the Association for Women in Mathematics (AWM) in 2015 for her mentorship of women in mathematics. In 2017 she was elected President of the AWM.

[[Rene Sylva]]

CATEGORIES: 1929 births, American botanists, Scientists from Hawaii, People from Maui, 2008 deaths

Rene Sylva (January 1929 – December 28, 2008) was an American botanist. He was born in Paia, Hawaii. He was among the only native Hawaiian fishermen to speak in favor of a ban on fishing green sea turtles. 

After giving up a career in turtle fishing, he became involved in the conservation of native Hawaiian ecosystems. He was important for the surveying remote regions of the Hawaiian Islands for native plants.

Anita Borg (January 17, 1949 – April 6, 2003) was an American computer scientist. She founded the Institute for Women and Technology and the Grace Hopper Celebration of Women in Computing.

[[Jack Kehoe]]

Jack Kehoe (November 21, 1934 – January 14, 2020) was an American actor. He was born in California. His best known roles were in Serpico (1973), The Pope of Greenwich Village (1984) and Brian De Palma's The Untouchables (1987), as well as the cult favorites Car Wash (1976) and Midnight Run (1988), the popular western Young Guns II (1990), and On the Nickel (1980).

[[Liu Zhongyi]]

Liu died on 5 January 2020 in Beijing at the age of 89.

[[John Klyberg]]

CATEGORIES: 1931 births, 2020 deaths, Anglican bishops, English Anglicans, English priests, English Roman Catholics, People from London, Roman Catholic priests

Charles John Klyberg (29 July 1931 – 17 January 2020) was a British Roman Catholic priest and former Anglican bishop. From 1985 to 1996, he was the Bishop of Fulham in the Church of England. He studied at Lincoln Theological College, a Church of England theological college. 

In 1994, the gay rights campaign group OutRage! named Klyberg as one of ten closeted homosexual bishops in the Church of England.

In 1996, after retiring from Anglican ministry, Klyberg was received into the Roman Catholic Church. He later became a priest. He was made a Prelate of Honour by Pope John Paul II.

Klyberg died on 17 January 2020 in London at the age of 88.

[[SHA-1]]

SHA-1 is a mathematical algorithm to hash a certain string, which creates a one-way change from the source string to the result. It is commonly used for security and data loss, but there may be other cases. Computer programs exist to crack SHA-1 hashes by hashing random strings and storing the result. An example SHA-1 hash is "664add438097fbd4307f814de8e62a10f8905588" (the string "Wikipedia" hashed using SHA-1).

[[Cobble (geology)]]

A cobble (sometimes a cobblestone) is a clast of rock defined on the Udden–Wentworth scale as having a particle size of 64–256 millimeters (2.5–10.1 in), larger than a pebble and smaller than a boulder. Other scales define a cobble's size in slightly different terms. A rock made predominantly of cobbles is termed a conglomerate. Cobblestone is a building material based on cobbles.

[[Alfred Körner]]

CATEGORIES: 1926 births, 2020 deaths, 1948 Summer Olympics, 1954 FIFA World Cup players, 1958 FIFA World Cup players, Austrian footballers, Austrian football managers, Sportspeople from Vienna

Alfred Körner (14 February 1926 – 23 January 2020) was an Austrian footballer. He played as a striker. He was the younger brother of fellow international Robert Körner.

Körner was born in Vienna. He had a successful career with Rapid Wien between the mid-1940s and 1959. He won seven league titles with the club. He also played for the Austria national team from 1946 to 1958. He played in the 1954 FIFA World Cup, where Austria finished third, and the 1958 FIFA World Cup. He earned 47 caps for his country, scoring 14 goals.

Körner died on 23 January 2020 in Vienna. He was 93.

[[Toshiko Akiyoshi]]

CATEGORIES: 1929 births, Living people, American autobiographers, American bandleaders, American jazz musicians, American pianists, Japanese composers, Japanese pianists

Toshiko Akiyoshi is a Japanese-American jazz musician. She is a pianist, composer, arranger and bandleader. She has been nominated for fourteen Grammy Awards.  She was the first woman to win best arranger and composer awards in DownBeat magazine's annual readers' poll. In 1996, she published her autobiography, Life with Jazz.

Akiyoshi was born in Liaoyang, Manchuria, China. After the end of World War II, she moved to Beppu with her family.

[[Alfred Teinitzer]]

CATEGORIES: 1929 births, 2021 deaths, 1954 FIFA World Cup players, Austrian footballers, Sportspeople from Vienna

Alfred Teinitzer (29 July 1929 - 20 April 2021) was an Austrian footballer. He played as a midfielder.

Teinitzer was born in Vienna. He played club football for Rapid Wien and LASK Linz. He also played for the Austria national team. He was part of the squad that finished third in the 1954 FIFA World Cup.

[[Anglo-Frisian languages]]

CATEGORIES: West Germanic languages

The Anglo-Frisian languages are west-germanic languges, which include Anglic (or English) and Frisian. They are different from other West Germanic languages because of a number of sound changes. This is an old classification, which classified the germanic languages into the Anglo-Frisian languages, and Germanic languages (such as German).

Since about the 1960s, the model is that there was a language called North Sea Germanic, which included all of these.

[[Anglic languages]]

CATEGORIES: West Germanic languages

Anglic languages are West Germanic languages that come from Old English. They were first spoken on the British Isles. Creole languages based on forms of English are generally not included. Except for English, this group also includes Scots in Scotland, and Yola and Fingallan in Ireland.

[[Shibuya Junior and Senior High School]]

CATEGORIES: Education in Japan, Tokyo

Shibuya Junior and Senior High School (Shibuya Kyōiku Gakuen Shibuya Chūgaku Kōtō Gakkō) is a private co-ed secondary school in Shibuya Ward, Tokyo, Japan. People commonly call the school Shibu-Shibu for short. Only the junior high school accepts new students. The senior high school only accepts students coming up from the junior high school. Students go to each school for three years (for a total of six years).

Makuhari Junior and Senior High School (Chiba City, Chiba, Japan) is a sister school of Shibuya Junior and Senior High School. Both schools have the same school motto and educational objectives.

[[Masters of Computer Applications]]

CATEGORIES: Computer science

A Master of Computer Application (MCA) is a postgraduate degree in computer application awarded in India. It is a three year (6 semester) for all eligible bachelor degree holders and two year (4 semester) course for candidates having Bachelor of Computer Application (BCA) or B.Sc (IT) degree. The students entering MCA must have a bachelor degree with Mathematics as one of the subjects at higher secondary or graduation. The program is a blend of both theoretical and practical knowledge.

An MCA degree endows students’ an opportunity  to work with tools meant to develop better and faster applications.

Designed to meet the shortage of qualified professionals in the IT (Information Technology) industry, an MCA degree - in India - is offered by many colleges. Infact, there are various colleges that also offer integrated MCA program as well.

[[Luling, Texas]]

CATEGORIES: Cities in Texas
